{"title_page": "Girolamo Prigione", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Archbishop\n| name        = Girolamo Prigione\n| title       = Titular Archbishop of  Lauriacum\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese     = \n| see         = Titular See of  Lauriacum\n| term        = 1968 \u2013 2016\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = 18 May 1944\n| consecration   = 24 November 1968\n| consecrated_by = [[Amleto Giovanni Cicognani|Amleto Giovanni Cardinal Cicognani]]\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1921|10|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Castellazzo Bormida]], Italy\n| death_date    =27 May 2016 (aged 94)\n| death_place   =[[Alessandria]], Italy\n| previous_post = \n| ordinated_by   = \n}}\n\n'''Girolamo Prigione''' (12 October 1921 \u2013 27 May 2016) was an Italian [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] who worked in the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] from 1951 to 1997. He became an archbishop in 1968 and from then until retirement held positions at the rank of apostolic delegate or apostolic nuncio in several countries, including almost twenty years in Mexico where he became a controversial figure.\n\n==Early years==\nPrigione was born in [[Castellazzo Bormida]] and ordained a priest on 18 May 1944. He entered the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] in 1951.<ref name=cns/> He fulfilled assignments in Italy, Great Britain, the United States and Austria, and also served as a delegate at the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] in Vienna.<ref name=cns/>\n\n[[Pope Paul VI]] appointed him [[Titular Archbishop]] of [[Lauriacum]] and [[Apostolic Nuncio]] to [[El Salvador]] and [[Guatemala]] on 27 August 1968. He received his episcopal consecration on 24 November 1968 from Cardinal [[Amleto Giovanni Cicognani]].\n\nHe was appointed [[Apostolic Delegate]] to Ghana and Nigeria (a single title) on 2 October 1973.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | pages= 571, 628\u20139 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-65-1973-ocr.pdf | date= 1973 | volume = LXV }}</ref>{{efn|On 2 October 1973 he was named Delegate to West Central Africa, which became the Delegation to Ghana and Nigeria on 10 December.}}\n\nOn 29 April 1976, he was named Apostolic Pro-Nuncio to Nigeria.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | page= 365| url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-68-1976-ocr.pdf | date= 1976 | volume = LXVIII }}</ref>\n\n==Mexico years==\nPope Paul named him [[Apostolic Nuncio to Mexico|Apostolic Delegate to Mexico]] on 7 February 1978.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | page= 210| url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-70-1978-ocr.pdf | date= 1978 | volume = LXX }}</ref> Prigione played an important role in giving the Mexican episcopate a more conservative profile in line with [[Pope John Paul II]]'s repression of [[liberation theology]] and reassertion of papal primacy. When Archbishop of Chihuahua [[Adalberto Almeida y Merino]] denounced electoral fraud in the 1986 gubernatorial elections, he announced the closing of churches in the diocese on July 20. Prigione moved to avert a replay of the Church-State conflict of the late 1920s.<ref>Vikram K. Chand, ''Mexico's Political Awakening''. Notre Dame: University of Notre Dame Press 2001, p. 183.</ref>\n\nWhen Prigione arrived in Mexico the Holy See and the Mexican government did not have diplomatic relations and the Church functioned in the country only because the government chose not to enforce much of its anti-religious law. Prigione was a key player in the change in attitude and policy of the Mexican government toward the Catholic Church. He was engaged in secret talks with the government in the month before the inauguration of [[List of heads of state of Mexico|President]] [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] in December 1988. The [[Holy See]] and Mexico established diplomatic relations in September 1992 after lengthy negotiations and  major changes to the stringent anti-clerical provisions of the Mexican [[Constitution of 1917]] in December 1991.<ref>{{cite news| access-date = 29 April 2019 | work = New York Times |title= Mexico Ending Church Restraints After 70 Years of Official Hostility | first = Tim | last = Golden |date=20 December 1991| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/20/world/mexico-ending-church-restraints-after-70-years-of-official-hostility.html }}</ref><ref>Chand, ''Mexico's Political Awakening'', p. 197.</ref> During his visit to Mexico in May 1990 Pope John Paul had announced an upgrade of Prigione's status from apostolic delegate to permanent special envoy.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = 29 April 2019 |title= Pope, in Mexico, Preaches Harmony| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/09/world/pope-in-mexico-preaches-harmony.html | date = 9 May 1990 | first = Larry | last = Rohter}}</ref> He made Prigione Apostolic Nuncio to Mexico on 12 October 1992.\n\nIn December 1993 and January 1994, Prigione met with secretly with two drug traffickers the government had identified as culpable in the assassination of Cardinal [[Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo]] in May 1993.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/110930/fallece-sacerdote-que-reunio-a-los-arellano-felix-con-prigione|publisher=Proceso|title=Fallece sacerdote que reuni\u00f3 a los Arellano Felix con Prigione|language=Spanish|trans-title=Priest who arranged renunion of Arellano-Felix brothers and Prigione dies|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref> He said he had not heard their confessions but that \"As I am accustomed to do with people, I received them in private and listened to them ... I am obliged to keep secret that which people confide in me in private.\" His actions fueled tensions with the government as some Catholic priests were being accused of supporting a [[Zapatista Army of National Liberation|rebel movement]].<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/29/world/pope-s-envoy-in-mexico-met-hunted-men.html | work = New York Times | date= 29 July 1994| title = Pope's Envoy In Mexico Met Hunted Men | first = Anthony | last = Depalma}}</ref> He was sharply criticized by both political and church officials.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/07/world/mexico-s-drug-fight-lagging-with-graft-given-as-a-cause.html | work = New York Times | date = 7 August 1994 | title = Mexico's Drug Fight Lagging, With Graft Given as a Cause | first = Tim | last = Golden}}</ref> The next year, when Bishop [[Samuel Ruiz Garcia]] of San Cristobal was accused of supporting the rebels, Mexico's bishops divided into opposing camps, some seeing the charge as scapegoating and the others, led by Prigione, distancing themselves and the Church from Ruiz.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = 29 April 2019 |date= 19 February 1995|  url = https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/19/world/the-dear-father-of-mexican-indians-is-the-assassin-bishop-to-his-foes.html | title =The 'Dear Father' of Mexican Indians Is the 'Assassin Bishop' to His Foes| first = Anthony | last = Depalma}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nHe retired on 2 April 1997 with the appointment of Archbishop [[Justo Mullor Garc\u00eda]] to succeed him as Nuncio to Mexico. He died on 27 May 2016 in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Alessandria|Diocese of Alessandria]] in Italy.<ref name=cns>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 | date = 27 May 2016 | url = https://www.catholicregister.org/home/international/item/22400-archbishops-prigione-first-nuncio-to-mexico-dies-in-italy | publisher = Catholic Register | agency = Catholic News Service | title = Archbishop Prigione, first nuncio to Mexico, dies in Italy}}</ref>\n\nHis reputation in Mexico was largely political, and the Mexican press reflected this when reporting his death. ''El Universal'' mentioned the restoration of diplomatic ties, meeting with drug lords, and the cardinal's assassination, and called him \"controversial\".<ref>{{cite news | language= es | access-date = 29 April 2019 |date= 27 May 2016 |work = El Universal |  url = https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/sociedad/2016/05/27/girolamo-prigione-polemico-primer-nuncio-apostolico-en-mexico | title = Giralomo Prigione, pol\u00e9mico primer Nuncio Apost\u00f3lico en M\u00e9xico}}</ref> ''Proceso'' mentioned the drug lords and said Prigione had protected the sexual abuser [[Marcial Maciel]]. It weighed the positive diplomacy against his negative role in Mexico's internal affairs. It charged him with supporting the government against progressives in the Church and called his years in Mexico \"a long period of ecclesiastical subjugation\". It characterized the bishops whose appointments he championed as hard-liners and noted that one still survived, the Cardinal Archbishop of Mexico [[Norberto Rivera Carrera]].<ref>{{cite news | language= es| work = Proceso | access-date = 29 April 2019 | date= 27 May 2016 | url = https://www.proceso.com.mx/441937/muere-a-los-94-anos-girolamo-prigione-primer-nuncio-apostolico-en-mexico | title = Muere Prigione, el nuncio que se entrevist\u00f3 con narcos y encubri\u00f3 al padre Maciel |first= Rodrigo | last = Vera }}</ref> When [[Pope Francis]] accepted the resignation of Rivera in December 2017, ''El Economist'' headlined its report: \"Goodbye to Prigione's Princes\". It said Prigione had united the Church with the government \"to disrupt everything that smells of liberation theology and all pastoral work that brings the faithful closer to political participation or social organization\".<ref>{{cite news | language=es | access-date = 29 April 2019 | url = https://www.eleconomista.com.mx/opinion/Adios-a-los-principes-de-Prigione-20171222-0033.html | date= 22 December 2017 | title = Adi\u00f3s a los pr\u00edncipes de Prigione | first = Diego | last = Petersen Farah}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bprigione.html Catholic-Hierarchy] [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n\n<!-- Navboxes go here -->\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prigione, Girolamo}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Mexico]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Ghana]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Italian titular archbishops]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Archbishop\n| name        = Girolamo Prigione\n| title       = Titular Archbishop of  Lauriacum\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| church      = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = \n| diocese     = \n| see         = Titular See of  Lauriacum\n| term        = 1968 \u2013 2016\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = 18 May 1944\n| consecration   = 24 November 1968\n| consecrated_by = [[Amleto Giovanni Cicognani|Amleto Giovanni Cardinal Cicognani]]\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1921|10|12|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Castellazzo Bormida]], Italy\n| death_date    =27 May 2016 (aged 94)\n| death_place   =[[Alessandria]], Italy\n| previous_post = \n| ordinated_by   = \n}}\n\n'''Girolamo Prigione''' (12 October 1921 \u2013 27 May 2016) was an Italian [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] who worked in the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] from 1951 to 1997. He became an archbishop in 1968 and from then until retirement held positions at the rank of apostolic delegate or apostolic nuncio in several countries, including almost twenty years in Mexico where he became a controversial figure.\n\n==Early years==\nPrigione was born in [[Castellazzo Bormida]] and ordained a priest on 18 May 1944. He entered the diplomatic service of the [[Holy See]] in 1951.<ref name=cns/> He fulfilled assignments in Italy, Great Britain, the United States and Austria, and also served as a delegate at the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] in Vienna.<ref name=cns/>\n\n[[Pope Paul VI]] appointed him [[Titular Archbishop]] of [[Lauriacum]] and [[Apostolic Nuncio]] to [[El Salvador]] and [[Guatemala]] on 27 August 1968. He received his episcopal consecration on 24 November 1968 from Cardinal [[Amleto Giovanni Cicognani]].\n\nHe was appointed [[Apostolic Delegate]] to Ghana and Nigeria (a single title) on 2 October 1973.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | pages= 571, 628\u20139 | url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-65-1973-ocr.pdf | date= 1973 | volume = LXV }}</ref>{{efn|On 2 October 1973 he was named Delegate to West Central Africa, which became the Delegation to Ghana and Nigeria on 10 December.}}\n\nOn 29 April 1976, he was named Apostolic Pro-Nuncio to Nigeria.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | page= 365| url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-68-1976-ocr.pdf | date= 1976 | volume = LXVIII }}</ref>\n\n==Mexico years==\nPope Paul named him [[Apostolic Nuncio to Mexico|Apostolic Delegate to Mexico]] on 7 February 1978.<ref>{{cite book | title = Acta Apostolicae Sedis | page= 210| url = https://www.vatican.va/archive/aas/documents/AAS-70-1978-ocr.pdf | date= 1978 | volume = LXX }}</ref> Prigione played an important role in giving the Mexican episcopate a more conservative profile in line with [[Pope John Paul II]]'s repression of [[liberation theology]] and reassertion of papal primacy. When Archbishop of Chihuahua [[Adalberto Almeida y Merino]] denounced electoral fraud in the 1986 gubernatorial elections, he announced the closing of churches in the diocese on July 20. Prigione moved to avert a replay of the Church-State conflict of the late 1920s.<ref>Vikram K. Chand, ''Mexico's Political Awakening''. Notre Dame: University of Notre Dame Press 2001, p. 183.</ref>\n\nWhen Prigione arrived in Mexico the Holy See and the Mexican government did not have diplomatic relations and the Church functioned in the country only because the government chose not to enforce much of its anti-religious law. Prigione was a key player in the change in attitude and policy of the Mexican government toward the Catholic Church. He was engaged in secret talks with the government in the month before the inauguration of President [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] in December 1988. The [[Holy See]] and Mexico established diplomatic relations in September 1992 after lengthy negotiations and  major changes to the stringent anti-clerical provisions of the Mexican [[Constitution of 1917]] in December 1991.<ref>{{cite news| access-date = 29 April 2019 | work = New York Times |title= Mexico Ending Church Restraints After 70 Years of Official Hostility | first = Tim | last = Golden |date=20 December 1991| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/20/world/mexico-ending-church-restraints-after-70-years-of-official-hostility.html }}</ref><ref>Chand, ''Mexico's Political Awakening'', p. 197.</ref> During his visit to Mexico in May 1990 Pope John Paul had announced an upgrade of Prigione's status from apostolic delegate to permanent special envoy.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = 29 April 2019 |title= Pope, in Mexico, Preaches Harmony| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1990/05/09/world/pope-in-mexico-preaches-harmony.html | date = 9 May 1990 | first = Larry | last = Rohter}}</ref> He made Prigione Apostolic Nuncio to Mexico on 12 October 1992.\n\nIn December 1993 and January 1994, Prigione met with secretly with two drug traffickers the government had identified as culpable in the assassination of Cardinal [[Juan Jesus Posadas Ocampo]] in May 1993.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/110930/fallece-sacerdote-que-reunio-a-los-arellano-felix-con-prigione|publisher=Proceso|title=Fallece sacerdote que reuni\u00f3 a los Arellano Felix con Prigione|language=Spanish|trans-title=Priest who arranged renunion of Arellano-Felix brothers and Prigione dies|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=June 1, 2019}}</ref> He said he had not heard their confessions but that \"As I am accustomed to do with people, I received them in private and listened to them ... I am obliged to keep secret that which people confide in me in private.\" His actions fueled tensions with the government as some Catholic priests were being accused of supporting a [[Zapatista Army of National Liberation|rebel movement]].<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/29/world/pope-s-envoy-in-mexico-met-hunted-men.html | work = New York Times | date= 29 July 1994| title = Pope's Envoy In Mexico Met Hunted Men | first = Anthony | last = Depalma}}</ref> He was sharply criticized by both political and church officials.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 |url = https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/07/world/mexico-s-drug-fight-lagging-with-graft-given-as-a-cause.html | work = New York Times | date = 7 August 1994 | title = Mexico's Drug Fight Lagging, With Graft Given as a Cause | first = Tim | last = Golden}}</ref> The next year, when Bishop [[Samuel Ruiz Garcia]] of San Cristobal was accused of supporting the rebels, Mexico's bishops divided into opposing camps, some seeing the charge as scapegoating and the others, led by Prigione, distancing themselves and the Church from Ruiz.<ref>{{cite news | work= New York Times | access-date = 29 April 2019 |date= 19 February 1995|  url = https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/19/world/the-dear-father-of-mexican-indians-is-the-assassin-bishop-to-his-foes.html | title =The 'Dear Father' of Mexican Indians Is the 'Assassin Bishop' to His Foes| first = Anthony | last = Depalma}}</ref>\n\n==Last years==\nHe retired on 2 April 1997 with the appointment of Archbishop [[Justo Mullor Garc\u00eda]] to succeed him as Nuncio to Mexico. He died on 27 May 2016 in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Alessandria|Diocese of Alessandria]] in Italy.<ref name=cns>{{cite news | access-date = 29 April 2019 | date = 27 May 2016 | url = https://www.catholicregister.org/home/international/item/22400-archbishops-prigione-first-nuncio-to-mexico-dies-in-italy | publisher = Catholic Register | agency = Catholic News Service | title = Archbishop Prigione, first nuncio to Mexico, dies in Italy}}</ref>\n\nHis reputation in Mexico was largely political, and the Mexican press reflected this when reporting his death. ''El Universal'' mentioned the restoration of diplomatic ties, meeting with drug lords, and the cardinal's assassination, and called him \"controversial\".<ref>{{cite news | language= es | access-date = 29 April 2019 |date= 27 May 2016 |work = El Universal |  url = https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/nacion/sociedad/2016/05/27/girolamo-prigione-polemico-primer-nuncio-apostolico-en-mexico | title = Giralomo Prigione, pol\u00e9mico primer Nuncio Apost\u00f3lico en M\u00e9xico}}</ref> ''Proceso'' mentioned the drug lords and said Prigione had protected the sexual abuser [[Marcial Maciel]]. It weighed the positive diplomacy against his negative role in Mexico's internal affairs. It charged him with supporting the government against progressives in the Church and called his years in Mexico \"a long period of ecclesiastical subjugation\". It characterized the bishops whose appointments he championed as hard-liners and noted that one still survived, the Cardinal Archbishop of Mexico [[Norberto Rivera Carrera]].<ref>{{cite news | language= es| work = Proceso | access-date = 29 April 2019 | date= 27 May 2016 | url = https://www.proceso.com.mx/441937/muere-a-los-94-anos-girolamo-prigione-primer-nuncio-apostolico-en-mexico | title = Muere Prigione, el nuncio que se entrevist\u00f3 con narcos y encubri\u00f3 al padre Maciel |first= Rodrigo | last = Vera }}</ref> When [[Pope Francis]] accepted the resignation of Rivera in December 2017, ''El Economist'' headlined its report: \"Goodbye to Prigione's Princes\". It said Prigione had united the Church with the government \"to disrupt everything that smells of liberation theology and all pastoral work that brings the faithful closer to political participation or social organization\".<ref>{{cite news | language=es | access-date = 29 April 2019 | url = https://www.eleconomista.com.mx/opinion/Adios-a-los-principes-de-Prigione-20171222-0033.html | date= 22 December 2017 | title = Adi\u00f3s a los pr\u00edncipes de Prigione | first = Diego | last = Petersen Farah}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bprigione.html Catholic-Hierarchy] [[Wikipedia:SPS|{{sup|[''self-published'']}}]]\n\n<!-- Navboxes go here -->\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Italy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prigione, Girolamo}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to El Salvador]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Mexico]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Guatemala]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Ghana]]\n[[Category:Apostolic Nuncios to Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Italian titular archbishops]]\n", "name_user": "Amqui", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMexico years:+wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Girolamo_Prigione"}
{"title_page": "List of Xiaomi products", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| logo = Xiaomi logo.svg\n| logo_size = 120px\n| founder = [[Lei Jun]]\n| products = Mi Tv <br />\n\nMi NoteBook <br />\n\nMi Band <br />\n\nMi drone <br />\n\nMi WiFi <br />\n\nMi Box <br />\n\nRedmi <br />\n\nPoco <br />\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2010|04|06|df=y}}\n}}\n[[Xiaomi]] produces smartphones (Mi Series, Mi Note Series, Mi Max Series, Mi Mix Series and [[Redmi|Redmi Series]]), tablets, laptops, wearable devices, TVs, routers and other smart home devices on their web store and on third-party websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-09/xiaomi-confronts-counterfeits-as-fake-products-eat-into-sales|title=Xiaomi Confronts Counterfeits as Fake Products Eat Into Sales - Bloomberg Business|date=10 April 2015|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413082926/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-09/xiaomi-confronts-counterfeits-as-fake-products-eat-into-sales |archivedate=13 April 2015|url-status=live|accessdate=28 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some of their products are listed below.\n\n<!--Please do not include devices made by Xiaomi-affiliated manufacturers in the list (e.g., Xiaomi Smart Home, Xiaomi Life, Mijia, Xiaomi Ecosystem, Xiaomi Shengtailian, Xiaomi Youpin, Xiaomi Crowdfunding), they are not manufactured by Xiaomi itself.-->\n\n== Smartphones ==\n=== MIUI ===\n{{Main|MIUI}}Xiaomi's smartphones run MIUI. [[MIUI]] is a stock and aftermarket Android firmware for [[smartphones]] and [[tablet computers]] based on the [[open-source]] [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[operating system]]. It is available on Xiaomi devices as well as devices made by other companies. It is Xiaomi's earliest known product.\n\n=== Mi Series ===\nXiaomi's flagship mobile handset line is the Xiaomi Mi series.\n\nThe Mi 3 uses a modified [[Qualcomm Snapdragon]] 800 and was found on test to be the world's fastest Android smartphone according to [[Benchmark (computing)|benchmark]] testing apps [[Antutu]], Quadrant, and [[Geekbench]].<ref>{{citation|title=Xiaomi - Google+ - A comparison between # XiaoMi3 and other flagship\u2026|date=25 November 2013|url=https://plus.google.com/112108000562542116245/posts/e4sbTVSiPs2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416205343/https://plus.google.com/112108000562542116245/posts/e4sbTVSiPs2|url-status=live|accessdate=15 April 2014|archivedate=16 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nXiaomi showcased its ceramic [[Xiaomi Mi 5|Mi 5]] on 24 February at MWC 2016. It is also equipped with [[Near-field communication|NFC]] and a mobile payment function [[Mi-Pay|Mi Pay]] launched in April 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://allchinatech.com/8652-2/|title=Xiaomi to launch Mi Pay to take on Apple Pay|date=21 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424152953/http://www.allchinatech.com/8652-2/ |archivedate=24 April 2016|url-status=live|publisher=allchinatech.com|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2016, Xiaomi released the Mi 5s and Mi 5s Plus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/xiaomi_launches_mi_5s_and_mi_5s_plus-news-20730.php|title=Xiaomi launches Mi 5s and Mi 5s Plus|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160928172015/http://www.gsmarena.com/xiaomi_launches_mi_5s_and_mi_5s_plus-news-20730.php|archivedate=28 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 November 2016, Xiaomi released the [[Xiaomi Mi MIX|Mi MIX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/25/13401440/xiaomi-mi-mix-concept-phone-specs-release-date-price|title=Xiaomi is selling the concept phone of your wildest dreams|website=The Verge|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119142131/https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/25/13401440/xiaomi-mi-mix-concept-phone-specs-release-date-price|archivedate=19 November 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mi mix is characterized by a 91.3% screen to body ratio, which was achieved by removing all the top-mounted sensors: the [[proximity sensor]] has been replaced by ultrasound, the earpiece has been replaced with a [[piezoelectric speaker]] that uses the metal frame to generate sound, and the front-facing camera is relocated to the bottom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/xiaomi_mi_mix-8400.php|title=Xiaomi Mi Mix|publisher=gsmarena.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324051333/http://www.gsmarena.com/xiaomi_mi_mix-8400.php|archivedate=24 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Xiaomi Mi 5c]] was launched on February 2017, featuring the debut of Xiaomi's in-house processor, Pinecone Surge S1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/xiaomi-mi-5c-4048|title=Xiaomi Mi 5c price, specifications, features, comparison|website=NDTV Gadgets360.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170328195503/http://gadgets.ndtv.com/xiaomi-mi-5c-4048|archivedate=28 March 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.trustedreviews.com/news/xiaomi-mi5c-surge-s1-news-specs-release-date-price-2954175|title=Xiaomi Mi 5C: All you need to know about the Surge S1-powered phone {{!}} Trusted Reviews|date=2017-02-28|work=Trusted Reviews|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[Xiaomi Mi 9]] was launched on 20 February 2019 in Beijing, China. This is Xiaomi's first triple camera smartphone. It is Powered By [[List of Qualcomm Snapdragon systems-on-chip|Snapdragon 855]] SoC with 8GB [[Random-access memory|RAM]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.androidleo.com/xiaomi-mi9-specs-price/|title=Xiaomi Mi 9 Full specifications, Price|date=2019-02-21|work=Androidleo.com|access-date=2019-02-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Model\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Display type\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Display size\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Resolution\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Release date\n! rowspan=\"2\" |[[Long Term Evolution