108/http://venturebeat.com/2014/07/22/chinese-smartphone-maker-xiaomi-launches-sleek-new-phone-and-13-fitness-band/|archivedate=30 April 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> With 2.8 million Mi Band shipments in the first quarter of 2015, Xiaomi became the world's second-largest wearables maker, accounting for 24.6% of the global market share.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jun/04/xiaomi-worlds-second-biggest-wearables-maker|title=Xiaomi now world's second-biggest wearables maker|last1=Gibbs|first1=Samuel|date=4 June 2015|work=The Guardian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209182010/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jun/04/xiaomi-worlds-second-biggest-wearables-maker|archivedate=9 December 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nXiaomi announced the Mi Band 2 in June 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2016/6/2/11840394/xiaomi-mi-band-2-official|title=Xiaomi officially launches the Mi Band 2|work=The Verge|access-date=24 November 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201040358/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2016/6/2/11840394/xiaomi-mi-band-2-official|archivedate=1 December 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Mi Band 2 features [[Photoplethysmogram|PPG]] sensor for accurate heart rate tracking. It also uses an upgraded pedometer algorithm for gathering better fitness and sleep data. The Mi Band 2's housing was rated for [[IP67]] water resistance.\n\nThe Mi Band 3 was released 18 July 2018. It has a larger battery, larger screen and improved water resistance.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techadvisor.co.uk/new-product/wearable-tech/xiaomi-mi-band-3-3678215/|title=Pre-order the Mi Band 3 fitness tracker|last=Macro|first=Ashleigh|work=Tech Advisor|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"Xiaomi Mi Band 3 review\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.techradar.com/uk/reviews/xiaomi-mi-band-3-review|title=Xiaomi Mi Band 3 review|work=TechRadar|access-date=2018-08-03|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://geek360.com.br/melhores-smartbands/|title=Melhores Smartbands do Mercado, Atualizado para 2019 - Geek360|date=2018-10-10|website=Geek 360|language=pt-BR|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Model\n!Design\n!Display\n!Specifications\n!Release Date\n|-\n|[[Xiaomi Mi Band|Mi Band]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mi.com/en/miband/|title=Mi Band - Mi Global Home|publisher=mi.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825144318/http://www.mi.com/en/miband/|archivedate=25 August 2017|url-status=live|access-date=5 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|[[File:Mi_Band.jpg|150x150px|Mi Band]]\n|3 LED Multi Color\n|[[Pedometer]], Vibration\n|22 July 2014\n|-\n|[[Xiaomi Mi Band#Xiaomi Mi Band Pulse|Mi Band 1S]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mi.com/shouhuan/spec/|title=\u5c0f\u7c73\u667a\u80fd\u624b\u73af\u53c2\u6570 - \u5c0f\u7c73\u5546\u57ce|publisher=mi.com|language=zh-CN|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904063944/http://www.mi.com/shouhuan/spec/|archivedate=4 September 2017|url-status=live|access-date=5 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|[[File:Xiaomi_Mi_Band_Black.jpg|150x150px|Xiaomi Mi Band 1s]]\n|3 LED White\n|Pedometer, Heart Rate Monitor, Vibration\n|7 November 2015\n|-\n|[[Xiaomi Mi Band 2|Mi Band 2]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mi.com/en/miband2/|title=Mi Band 2 - Mi Global Home|date=10 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110085242/http://www.mi.com/en/miband2/|archivedate=10 November 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|access-date=29 January 2017}}</ref>\n|[[File:Xiaomi Mi band 2 18.jpg|frameless]]\n|0,42\" [[OLED]], [[Monochromatic]]\n|Watch, Heart Rate Monitor, Pedometer, Vibration, [[Touchpad]]\n|7 June 2016\n|-\n|Mi Band - HRX Edition<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mi.com/in/mi-band-hrx/|title=Mi India|publisher=mi.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027231945/http://www.mi.com/in/mi-band-hrx/|archivedate=27 October 2017|url-status=live|access-date=27 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|\n|0,42\" OLED, Monochromatic\n|Watch, Pedometer, Vibration, Touchpad\n|15 September 2017 (India)\n|-\n|[[Xiaomi Mi Band 3|Mi Band 3]]\n|[[File:Mi Band 3 NFC.jpeg|frameless]]\n|0.78\" [[OLED]], [[Monochromatic]]\n|Watch, Heart Rate Monitor, Pedometer, Vibration, [[Touchpad]], NFC (limited models)<ref name=\"Xiaomi Mi Band 3 review\"/>\n|18 July 2018\n|-\n|[[Xiaomi Mi Band 4|Mi Band 4]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gizmochina.com/2019/06/11/xiaomi-mi-band-4-officially-launched/|title=Xiaomi Mi Band 4 officially launched with AMOLED color Display & Cheap Price tag|last=Jaszly|first=Airyl|date=2019-06-11|website=Gizmochina|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n|\n|0.95\" [[AMOLED]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mi.com/shouhuan4/specs/|title=\u5c0f\u7c73\u624b\u73af4 \u53c2\u6570-\u5c0f\u7c73\u5546\u57ce|website=www.mi.com|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n|Watch, Heart Rate Monitor, Pedometer, Vibration, [[Touchpad]], [[Near-field communication|NFC]] (some models)<ref name=\":1\" />\n|14 June 2019 (China)\n26 June 2019 (Europe)\n|}\n\n== Mechanical Watch ==\nXiaomi released a mechanical watch called the CIGA Automatic Mechanical Watch. It has a square shape with rounded corners. The body is stainless steel and comes with a choice of black or silver. The watch comes with a metal mesh band or a leather strap. The mechanical movement is made by Seagull watch company. The watch was designed by Hong-Kong-based Michael Young and has won the German IF Design award.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.xiaomitoday.com/xiaomi-ciga-automatic-mechanical-watch-offered-for-180-99coupon/|title=Xiaomi CIGA Automatic Mechanical Watch Offered For $159.74|date=2018-09-19|work=XiaomiToday|access-date=2018-09-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Smart Home Products ==\n{{Main|Xiaomi Smart Home}}\n<!-- Insert summary of main article -->\nNote that products released by ''Xiaomi Smart Home'' are products of companies partnered with Xiaomi instead of Xiaomi themselves.<ref>[https://www.androidcentral.com/these-are-best-xiaomi-lifestyle-products-you-can-buy These are the best Xiaomi lifestyle products you can buy in 2018]</ref>\nIncludes [[robotic vacuum cleaner]]s and other goods.\n\nMi Home app  manages Xiaomi [[smart home]] products.\n\n== Mi Drone ==\nThe Mi Drone has a [[1080p]] camera and a [[4K resolution|4K camera]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mi.com/en/drone/|title=Mi Global Home|website=www.mi.com|language=en-EN|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127084204/http://www.mi.com/en/drone/|archivedate=27 January 2018|url-status=live|access-date=26 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It has a range of 2km while able to maintain a [[720p]] video stream.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/05/25/xiaomi-mi-drone/|title=Xiaomi's Mi Drone is pretty affordable for what it does|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-09-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Xiaomi]]\n*[https://kyadomain.blogspot.com/2019/06/redmi-note-8-pro-specifications.html?m=1 Xiaomi '''note 8 pro''' specifications]\n*[https://kyadomain.blogspot.com/2019/05/Xiaomi-Black-Shark-2-Gaming-Smartphone-Launch-Pricing-and-Specifications.html Gaming smartphones of Xiaomi]\n*\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Xiaomi]]\n[[Category:Lists of mobile phones|Xiaomi]]\n[[Category:Lists of products|Xiaomi]]\n[[Category:Lists of mobile computers|Xiaomi]]\n", "name_user": "Maksdroider", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Xiaomi_products"}
{"title_page": "Frank Szirmay", "text_new": "'''Frank Szirmay''' (1916 - 1985) was a Hungarian New Zealand sculptor. In 1956 Szirmay fled the Hungarian revolt with his family, and they emigrated to New Zealand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Bell|first=Leonard|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=hDA5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276&lpg=PT276&dq=Mart%C3%A9+Szirmay&source=bl&ots=UJ0juzx7gw&sig=ACfU3U1L4bjJxANvFlqEtLZzdyYpBxuIug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRoYfr0OboAhV36nMBHYfPBas4PBDoATAAegQICxAo#v=onepage&q=Mart%C3%A9%20Szirmay&f=false|title=Strangers Arrive: Emigr\u00e9s and the Arts in New Zealand, 1930\u20131980|date=2017-11-17|publisher=Auckland University Press|isbn=978-1-77558-954-9|language=en}}</ref> Szirmay's step-daughter is well-known sculptor [[Mart\u00e9 Szirmay]].\n[[File:Young Nick Statue Gisborne.jpg|alt=Young Nick statue, Gisborne.|thumb|221x221px|Young Nick statue, Gisborne.]]\n\n== Biography ==\nSzirmay began his career as a painter, but in the 1970s gained a national reputation as a sculptor of bronze figures in the [[Academic art|Academic Realist]] tradition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mare|first=Barbara|date=1989|title=Marte Szirmay: Paying Homage to the Organic|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1358207?origin=crossref|journal=Woman's Art Journal|volume=10|issue=2|pages=19|doi=10.2307/1358207|via=}}</ref> Szirmay taught art, and one of his most well-known pupils was [[Les Gibbard]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Szirmay's figurative sculptural style can be seen in a number of notable public commissions around New Zealand.\n\n== Notable works ==\n\n=== ''Young Nick'' ===\n[[File:Tangaroa, God of the sea.jpg|alt=Frank Szirmay'a representation of Tangaroa in bronze with Mount Maunganui in the background|thumb|187x187px|Frank Szirmay'a representation of Tangaroa in bronze with Mount Maunganui in the background.]]\n''Young Nick'' - bronze figure of [[Nicholas Young (sailor)|Nicholas Young]], unveiled in 1969 by [[Governor-General of New Zealand|Governor-General]] [[Arthur Porritt, Baron Porritt|Sir Arthur Porritt]] at Churchill Park on [[Waikanae|Waikanae Beach]], [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]] as part of the Cook Bicentenary Celebrations, which commemorated the first sighting of New Zealand on [[James Cook]]'s voyage in 1769.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://photonews.org.nz/gisborne/issue/GPN218_19720809/t1-front-d3.html|title=Our Cover|date=1972-08-09|work=Gisborne Photo News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The statue was gifted by the [[NZI|New Zealand Insurance Company]]. In 1988 the statue was moved to the mouth of the [[Turanganui River (Gisborne)|T\u016branganui River]], and is now positioned so that Young Nick points to [[Young Nick's Head|Young Nick's Head]] across the bay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.captaincooksociety.com/home/detail/waikanae-beach-gisborne-new-zealand|title=Waikanae Beach, Gisborne, New Zealand|website=The Captain Cook Society (CCS)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Tangaroa'' ===\n''Tangaroa'' - bronze figure of [[Tangaroa]], M\u0101ori God of the sea, installed in 1969. The status is situated at the entrance to [[Tauranga Harbour]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Tangaroa is portrayed as a crouching warrior grasping a [[taiaha]], and in recent years was moved to face harbour visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bayexplorer.co.nz/about-the-region/statue-of-tangaroa/|title=Bay Explorer {{!}} Maori God of the Sea {{!}} Statue of Tangaroa|website=Bay Explorer|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n[[File:Spirit of Napier, Napier, New Zealand.jpg|alt=The Gilray Fountain, better known as the Spirit of Napier, along Marine Parade in Napier, New Zealand.|thumb|190x190px|The Gilray Fountain, better known as the Spirit of Napier, along Marine Parade in Napier, New Zealand.]]\n\n=== ''The Spirit of Napier'' ===\n''The Spirit of Napier'' - bronze figure of a slender 'golden girl', with arms upraised on a high column. This work was installed in 1971 and memorialises Napier's rebirth after the devastating [[1931 Hawke's Bay earthquake|earthquake of 1931]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The statue was gifted to the city by the late Dr Thomas Gilray, a former superintendent of the Napier Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ahuriri-rotary.org.nz/spirit/spirit.html|title=Spirit of Napier|website=www.ahuriri-rotary.org.nz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2011 it was taken down by the Napier Council to be repaired after bronze rot was discovered.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carpinter|first=Bernard|url=|title=Years Unkind to Golden Girl|date=2011-05-07|work=The Dominion Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Discovery of New Zealand Chess Set'' ===\nAnother notable commission was a chess set, titled ''The Discovery of New Zealand Chess Set'', which depicts a peaceful meeting between M\u0101ori and Europeans, and was another work commissioned to commemorate the Cook Bicentenary. This work is held in the collection of [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/1609374|title=Loading... {{!}} Collections Online - Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|website=collections.tepapa.govt.nz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szirmay, Frank}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand artists]]\n", "text_old": "'''Frank Szirmay''' (1916 - 1985) was a Hungarian New Zealand sculptor. In 1956 Szirmay fled the Hungarian revolt with his family, and they emigrated to New Zealand.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Bell|first=Leonard|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=hDA5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276&lpg=PT276&dq=Mart%C3%A9+Szirmay&source=bl&ots=UJ0juzx7gw&sig=ACfU3U1L4bjJxANvFlqEtLZzdyYpBxuIug&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiRoYfr0OboAhV36nMBHYfPBas4PBDoATAAegQICxAo#v=onepage&q=Mart%C3%A9%20Szirmay&f=false|title=Strangers Arrive: Emigr\u00e9s and the Arts in New Zealand, 1930\u20131980|date=2017-11-17|publisher=Auckland University Press|isbn=978-1-77558-954-9|language=en}}</ref> Szirmay's step-daughter is well-known sculptor [[Mart\u00e9 Szirmay]].\n[[File:Young Nick Statue Gisborne.jpg|alt=Young Nick statue, Gisborne.|thumb|221x221px|Young Nick statue, Gisborne.]]\n\n== Biography ==\nSzirmay began his career as a painter, but in the 1970s gained a national reputation as a sculptor of bronze figures in the [[Academic art|Academic Realist]] tradition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mare|first=Barbara|date=1989|title=Marte Szirmay: Paying Homage to the Organic|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1358207?origin=crossref|journal=Woman's Art Journal|volume=10|issue=2|pages=19|doi=10.2307/1358207|via=}}</ref> Szirmay taught art, and one of his most well-known pupils was [[Les Gibbard]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Szirmay's figurative sculptural style can be seen in a number of notable public commissions around New Zealand.  \n\n== Notable works ==\n\n=== ''Young Nick'' ===\n[[File:Tangaroa, God of the sea.jpg|alt=Frank Szirmay'a representation of Tangaroa in bronze with Mount Maunganui in the background|thumb|187x187px|Frank Szirmay'a representation of Tangaroa in bronze with Mount Maunganui in the background.]]\n''Young Nick'' - bronze figure of [[Nicholas Young (sailor)|Nicholas Young]], unveiled in 1969 by [[Governor-General of New Zealand|Governor-General]] [[Arthur Porritt, Baron Porritt|Sir Arthur Porritt]] at Churchill Park on [[Waikanae|Waikanae Beach]], [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]] as part of the Cook Bicentenary Celebrations, which commemorated the first sighting of New Zealand on [[James Cook]]'s voyage in 1769.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://photonews.org.nz/gisborne/issue/GPN218_19720809/t1-front-d3.html|title=Our Cover|date=1972-08-09|work=Gisborne Photo News|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The statue was gifted by the [[NZI|New Zealand Insurance Company]]. In 1988 the statue was moved to the mouth of the [[Turanganui River (Gisborne)|T\u016branganui River]], and is now positioned so that Young Nick points to [[Young Nick's Head|Young Nick\u2019s Head]] across the bay.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.captaincooksociety.com/home/detail/waikanae-beach-gisborne-new-zealand|title=Waikanae Beach, Gisborne, New Zealand|website=The Captain Cook Society (CCS)|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Tangaroa'' ===\n''Tangaroa'' - bronze figure of [[Tangaroa]], M\u0101ori God of the sea, installed in 1969. The status is situated at the entrance to [[Tauranga Harbour]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Tangaroa is portrayed as a crouching warrior grasping a [[taiaha]], and in recent years was moved to face harbour visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bayexplorer.co.nz/about-the-region/statue-of-tangaroa/|title=Bay Explorer {{!}} Maori God of the Sea {{!}} Statue of Tangaroa|website=Bay Explorer|language=en-NZ|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n[[File:Spirit of Napier, Napier, New Zealand.jpg|alt=The Gilray Fountain, better known as the Spirit of Napier, along Marine Parade in Napier, New Zealand.|thumb|190x190px|The Gilray Fountain, better known as the Spirit of Napier, along Marine Parade in Napier, New Zealand.]]\n\n=== ''The Spirit of Napier'' ===\n''The Spirit of Napier'' - bronze figure of a slender 'golden girl', with arms upraised on a high column. This work was installed in 1971 and memorialises Napier's rebirth after the devastating [[1931 Hawke's Bay earthquake|earthquake of 1931]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The statue was gifted to the city by the late Dr Thomas Gilray, a former superintendent of the Napier Hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ahuriri-rotary.org.nz/spirit/spirit.html|title=Spirit of Napier|website=www.ahuriri-rotary.org.nz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> In 2011 it was taken down by the Napier Council to be repaired after bronze rot was discovered.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Carpinter|first=Bernard|url=|title=Years Unkind to Golden Girl|date=2011-05-07|work=The Dominion Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Discovery of New Zealand Chess Set'' ===\nAnother notable commission was a chess set, titled ''The Discovery of New Zealand Chess Set'', which depicts a peaceful meeting between M\u0101ori and Europeans, and was another work commissioned to commemorate the Cook Bicentenary. This work is held in the collection of [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/1609374|title=Loading... {{!}} Collections Online - Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|website=collections.tepapa.govt.nz|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szirmay, Frank}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand artists]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Szirmay"}
{"title_page": "Haggai", "text_new": "{{For|the prophetic book|Book of Haggai}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Short description|Hebrew prophet}}\n[[File:Haggai-prophet.jpg|thumb|[[Russian icon]] of Haggai, 18th century ([[Iconostasis]] of [[Kizhi]] [[monastery]], [[Karelia]], [[Russia]]).]]\n<!--  Commented out: [[Image:HebrewHaggai.jpg|thumb|{{deletable image-caption|Sunday, 2 May 2010}} Depiction of Haggai prophesying during the dedication of the Second Temple in Jerusalem.]] -->\n\n'''Haggai''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6|\u0261| a\u026a}}; {{lang-he-n|\u05d7\u05b7\u05d2\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9}} \u2013 ''\u1e24aggay''; [[Koine Greek]]: \u1f08\u03b3\u03b3\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-la|Aggaeus}}) was a [[Hebrew]] prophet during the building of the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]], and one of the twelve [[minor prophets]] in the [[Hebrew Bible]] and the author of the [[Book of Haggai]]. He is known for his prophecy in 520 BCE, commanding the Jews to rebuild the Temple.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Judaism in the Persian Period|last=Schiffman|first=Lawrence|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=53\u201354}}</ref> His name means \"my holiday.\" He was the first of three post-exile prophets from the Neo-Babylonian Exile of the House of Judah (with [[Zechariah (Hebrew prophet)|Zechariah]], his contemporary, and [[Malachi]], who lived about one hundred years later), who belonged to the period of [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|Jewish history]] which began after the return from [[Babylonian captivity|captivity]] in [[Babylon]].\n\nScarcely anything is known of his personal history. He may have been one of the [[Babylonian captivity|captives taken to Babylon]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II of Babylon|Nebuchadnezzar]]. He began God's prophecy about sixteen years after the [[Babylonian captivity#Return|return of the Jews to Judah]] (ca. 520 BCE). The work of rebuilding the [[Second Temple|temple]] had been put to a stop through the intrigues of the [[Samaritan]]s. After having been suspended for eighteen years, the work was resumed through the efforts of Haggai and Zechariah.<ref>{{Bibleverse||Ezra|6:14|131}}</ref> They exhorted the people, which roused them from their lethargy, and induced them to take advantage of a change in the policy of the Persian government under [[Darius I]].\n\nThe name Haggai, with various vocalizations, is also found in the [[Book of Esther]], as a [[Eunuch (court official)|eunuch]] servant of the [[Esther|Queen]].\n\n== Haggai Prophecies ==\n[[File:Tissot Haggai.jpg|thumb|150px|Haggai (watercolor circa 1896\u20131902 by [[James Tissot]])]]\nHaggai prophesied in 520 BCE Jerusalem, about the people needing to complete building the Temple. The new Temple was bound to exceed the awesomeness of the previous Temple. He claimed if the Temple was not built there would be poverty, famine and drought affecting the Jewish nation.\n\nThere is a controversy regarding who edited Haggai's works. According to scholars,  they credit it to his students. However, Jewish Tradition believe that the Men of the Great Assembly were responsible for the edits. The Men of the Great Assembly are traditionally known for continuing the work of Ezra and Nehemiah.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Haggai and officials of his time==\nHaggai supported the officials of his time, specifically [[Zerubbabel]], the governor, and [[Joshua the High Priest]]. In the Book of Haggai, God refers to Zerubbabel as \"my servant\" as King David was, and says he will make him as a \"signet ring,\" as King Jehoiachin was ({{bibleverse|Haggai|2:23|KJV}}; cf. {{bibleverse|Jer|22:24|KJV}}). The signet ring symbolized a ring worn on the hand of Yahweh, showing that a king held divine favour.  Thus, Haggai is implicitly, but not explicitly, saying that Zerubbabel would preside over a restored Davidic kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Michael |title=A Brief Introduction to the Old Testament |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2009 |page=346 |isbn=0195332725 }}</ref>\n\n== Jewish Persian Diplomacy ==\nThe Persian Empire was growing weak, and Haggai saw time as an opportunity to restore the Davidic Kingdom. He believed that the Kingdom of David was able to rise and take back their part in Jewish issues. Haggai's message was directed to the nobles and Zerubbabel, as he would be the first Davidic monarch restored. He saw this as important because the Kingdom would be an end to Jewish Idol worship.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Haggai in Jewish tradition==\nHaggai, in rabbinic writing, is often referred to as one of the men of the [[Great Assembly]]. The [[Babylonian Talmud]] (5th century CE) mentions a tradition concerning the prophet Haggai,<ref>Babylonian Talmud (''Yebamot'' 16a)</ref> saying that he gave instruction concerning three things: (a) that it is not lawful for a man whose brother married his daughter (as a co-wife in a polygamous relationship) to consummate a [[levirate marriage]] with one of his deceased brother's co-wives (a teaching accepted by the [[School of Hillel]], but rejected by the [[School of Shammai]]);<ref>A quintessential Jewish teaching, since it is lawful for a Jewish man to marry his brother's daughter, or his sister's daughter. Likewise, [[polygamy]] was permitted under [[Mosaic law]], as also the biblical injunction to take in marriage the wife of one's deceased brother (Heb. ''Yibum'' = levirate marriage) when they had no offspring. The problem, however, that arises here is that a man whose daughter was married to his brother, had his brother died childless, he (the living brother who is the father of his brother's wife) could not consummate a marriage with his own daughter, a thing prohibited in Jewish law, and therefore even the co-wives of his brother assume the same prohibition and are forbidden for him to marry.</ref> (b) that Jews living in the regions of [[Ammon]] and [[Moab]] separate from their produce the [[Poor tithe|poor man's tithe]] during the [[Sabbatical year (Bible)|Sabbatical year]]; (c) that they accept of proselytes from the peoples of [[Tadmor]] (Palmyra) and from the people of [[Kardu|\u1e32ardu]].\n\n== Liturgical commemoration ==\nOn the [[Eastern Orthodox liturgical calendar]], Haggai is commemorated as a [[saint]] and prophet. His [[feast day]] is 16 December (for those churches which follow the traditional [[Julian Calendar]], 16 December currently falls on 29 December of the modern [[Gregorian Calendar]]). He is also commemorated, in common with the other righteous persons of the Old Testament, on the Sunday of the Holy Fathers (the second Sunday before the [[Christmas|Nativity of the Lord]]).\n\nHaggai is commemorated with the other [[Minor prophet]]s in the [[Calendar of Saints (Armenian Apostolic Church)|Calendar of saints]] of the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] on 31 July.\n\n== Haggai in Freemasonry ==\nIn the Masonic degree of [[Holy Royal Arch]] Haggai is one of the Three Principals of the Chapter. Named after Haggai the prophet and accompanies [[Zerubbabel]], Prince of the People, and [[Joshua the High Priest|Joshua, the son of Josedech, the High Priest]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Book of Haggai]]\n*[[Tomb of the Prophets Haggai, Zechariah and Malachi]]\n\n== References ==\n* {{EBD|wstitle=Haggai}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ocafs.oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=103556 Prophet Haggai] Orthodox [[icon]] and [[synaxarion]]\n\n{{Prophets of the Tanakh}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:6th-century BC writers]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the Old Testament]]\n<!-- Don't need head category [[:Category:Prophets in Judaism]] or [[Category:Prophets in Christianity]], both hold sub-cat [[:Category:Prophets of the Hebrew Bible]] which is in the template {{Prophets of the Tanakh}} -->\n", "text_old": "{{For|the prophetic book|Book of Haggai}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Short description|Hebrew prophet}}\n[[File:Haggai-prophet.jpg|thumb|[[Russian icon]] of Haggai, 18th century ([[Iconostasis]] of [[Kizhi]] [[monastery]], [[Karelia]], [[Russia]]).]]\n<!--  Commented out: [[Image:HebrewHaggai.jpg|thumb|{{deletable image-caption|Sunday, 2 May 2010}} Depiction of Haggai prophesying during the dedication of the Second Temple in Jerusalem.]] -->\n\n'''Haggai''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6|\u0261| a\u026a}}; {{lang-he-n|\u05d7\u05b7\u05d2\u05b7\u05bc\u05d9}} \u2013 ''\u1e24aggay''; [[Koine Greek]]: \u1f08\u03b3\u03b3\u03b1\u1fd6\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-la|Aggaeus}}) was a [[Hebrew]] prophet during the building of the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]], and one of the twelve [[minor prophets]] in the [[Hebrew Bible]] and the author of the [[Book of Haggai]]. He is known for his prophecy in 520 BCE, commanding the Jews to rebuild the Temple.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Judaism in the Persian Period|last=Schiffman|first=Lawrence|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=53\u201354}}</ref> His name means \"my holiday.\" He was the first of three post-exile prophets from the Neo-Babylonian Exile of the House of Judah (with [[Zechariah (Hebrew prophet)|Zechariah]], his contemporary, and [[Malachi]], who lived about one hundred years later), who belonged to the period of [[History of ancient Israel and Judah|Jewish history]] which began after the return from [[Babylonian captivity|captivity]] in [[Babylon]].\n\nScarcely anything is known of his personal history. He may have been one of the [[Babylonian captivity|captives taken to Babylon]] by [[Nebuchadnezzar II of Babylon|Nebuchadnezzar]]. He began God's prophesy about sixteen years after the [[Babylonian captivity#Return|return of the Jews to Judah]] (ca. 520 BCE). The work of rebuilding the [[Second Temple|temple]] had been put to a stop through the intrigues of the [[Samaritan]]s. After having been suspended for eighteen years, the work was resumed through the efforts of Haggai and Zechariah.<ref>{{Bibleverse||Ezra|6:14|131}}</ref> They exhorted the people, which roused them from their lethargy, and induced them to take advantage of a change in the policy of the Persian government under [[Darius I]].\n\nThe name Haggai, with various vocalizations, is also found in the [[Book of Esther]], as a [[Eunuch (court official)|eunuch]] servant of the [[Esther|Queen]].\n\n== Haggai Prophecies ==\n[[File:Tissot Haggai.jpg|thumb|150px|Haggai (watercolor circa 1896\u20131902 by [[James Tissot]])]]\nHaggai prophesied in 520 BCE Jerusalem, about the people needing to complete building the Temple. The new Temple was bound to exceed the awesomeness of the previous Temple. He claimed if the Temple was not built there would be poverty, famine and drought affecting the Jewish nation.\n\nThere is a controversy regarding who edited Haggai's works. According to scholars,  they credit it to his students. However, Jewish Tradition believe that the Men of the Great Assembly were responsible for the edits. The Men of the Great Assembly are traditionally known for continuing the work of Ezra and Nehemiah.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Haggai and officials of his time==\nHaggai supported the officials of his time, specifically [[Zerubbabel]], the governor, and [[Joshua the High Priest]]. In the Book of Haggai, God refers to Zerubbabel as \"my servant\" as King David was, and says he will make him as a \"signet ring,\" as King Jehoiachin was ({{bibleverse|Haggai|2:23|KJV}}; cf. {{bibleverse|Jer|22:24|KJV}}). The signet ring symbolized a ring worn on the hand of Yahweh, showing that a king held divine favour.  Thus, Haggai is implicitly, but not explicitly, saying that Zerubbabel would preside over a restored Davidic kingdom.<ref>{{cite book |last=Coogan |first=Michael |title=A Brief Introduction to the Old Testament |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2009 |page=346 |isbn=0195332725 }}</ref>\n\n== Jewish Persian Diplomacy ==\nThe Persian Empire was growing weak, and Haggai saw time as an opportunity to restore the Davidic Kingdom. He believed that the Kingdom of David was able to rise and take back their part in Jewish issues. Haggai's message was directed to the nobles and Zerubbabel, as he would be the first Davidic monarch restored. He saw this as important because the Kingdom would be an end to Jewish Idol worship.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Haggai in Jewish tradition==\nHaggai, in rabbinic writing, is often referred to as one of the men of the [[Great Assembly]]. The [[Babylonian Talmud]] (5th century CE) mentions a tradition concerning the prophet Haggai,<ref>Babylonian Talmud (''Yebamot'' 16a)</ref> saying that he gave instruction concerning three things: (a) that it is not lawful for a man whose brother married his daughter (as a co-wife in a polygamous relationship) to consummate a [[levirate marriage]] with one of his deceased brother's co-wives (a teaching accepted by the [[School of Hillel]], but rejected by the [[School of Shammai]]);<ref>A quintessential Jewish teaching, since it is lawful for a Jewish man to marry his brother's daughter, or his sister's daughter. Likewise, [[polygamy]] was permitted under [[Mosaic law]], as also the biblical injunction to take in marriage the wife of one's deceased brother (Heb. ''Yibum'' = levirate marriage) when they had no offspring. The problem, however, that arises here is that a man whose daughter was married to his brother, had his brother died childless, he (the living brother who is the father of his brother's wife) could not consummate a marriage with his own daughter, a thing prohibited in Jewish law, and therefore even the co-wives of his brother assume the same prohibition and are forbidden for him to marry.</ref> (b) that Jews living in the regions of [[Ammon]] and [[Moab]] separate from their produce the [[Poor tithe|poor man's tithe]] during the [[Sabbatical year (Bible)|Sabbatical year]]; (c) that they accept of proselytes from the peoples of [[Tadmor]] (Palmyra) and from the people of [[Kardu|\u1e32ardu]].\n\n== Liturgical commemoration ==\nOn the [[Eastern Orthodox liturgical calendar]], Haggai is commemorated as a [[saint]] and prophet. His [[feast day]] is 16 December (for those churches which follow the traditional [[Julian Calendar]], 16 December currently falls on 29 December of the modern [[Gregorian Calendar]]). He is also commemorated, in common with the other righteous persons of the Old Testament, on the Sunday of the Holy Fathers (the second Sunday before the [[Christmas|Nativity of the Lord]]).\n\nHaggai is commemorated with the other [[Minor prophet]]s in the [[Calendar of Saints (Armenian Apostolic Church)|Calendar of saints]] of the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]] on 31 July.\n\n== Haggai in Freemasonry ==\nIn the Masonic degree of [[Holy Royal Arch]] Haggai is one of the Three Principals of the Chapter. Named after Haggai the prophet and accompanies [[Zerubbabel]], Prince of the People, and [[Joshua the High Priest|Joshua, the son of Josedech, the High Priest]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Book of Haggai]]\n*[[Tomb of the Prophets Haggai, Zechariah and Malachi]]\n\n== References ==\n* {{EBD|wstitle=Haggai}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ocafs.oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=103556 Prophet Haggai] Orthodox [[icon]] and [[synaxarion]]\n\n{{Prophets of the Tanakh}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:6th-century BC writers]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the Old Testament]]\n<!-- Don't need head category [[:Category:Prophets in Judaism]] or [[Category:Prophets in Christianity]], both hold sub-cat [[:Category:Prophets of the Hebrew Bible]] which is in the template {{Prophets of the Tanakh}} -->\n", "name_user": "Toweli", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haggai"}
{"title_page": "French occupation zone in Germany", "text_new": "{{Expand French|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''[[France|French]] occupation zone''' (in [[German language|German]]: ''Franz\u00f6sische Besatzungszone''), was one of the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied areas]] established in [[Germany]] after [[World War II]].\n\nFollowing the [[Armistice of the First World War]], [[Allies of the First World War|Allied]] forces occupied part of German territory until the [[1920s]] and France administered the [[Territory of the Saar Basin]] until 1935.\n\nThe strength of the occupying forces was 100,000 in the Rhine territories in the calmest periods. The maximum of soldiers was reached in May 1921 during the first occupation of [[Ruhrort]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]] with {{formatnum: 250000}} soldiers including {{formatnum: 210000}} French.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}[http://rha.revues.org/index6333.html Occupy Germany after 1918], ''[[Historical review of the armies]],'' 2009.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAt the end of the [[Second World War]], before the [[Yalta conference]] (4-11 February 1945), no occupation zone in Germany was to be allocated to France. At the insistence of [[Charles de Gaulle]] and [[Provisional Government of the French Republic]], [[Winston Churchill|Churchill]] obtained from [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] that an occupation zone was to be allocated to France provided that this consists of zones previously occupied by the Americans and the British:<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\">\n{{web link\n| url = http://docnum.univ-lorraine.fr/public/UPV-M/Theses/1994/Perrein_Engels.Helene.LMZ9412_1.pdf\n| format = Pdf\n| titre = The military presence in Germany from 1945 to 1993\n| author = H. Pennein-Engels\n| publisher = University of Metz - Faculty of Letters and Human Sciences\n| year = 1994\n| accessed on = July 8, 2015\n}}.</ref>\n\n; Extract from the final press release, Article 4:\n{{block quote | IV. Occupation zone for France and control council in Germany <br />\nIt was decided that an area of \u200b\u200bGermany would be allocated to France to be occupied by French forces. This zone would be taken from the British and American zones and its extent would be fixed by the British and the Americans, in agreement with the French Provisional Government.\n\nIt was also decided that the French Provisional Government would be invited to be part of the [[Allied Control Council|Allied Control Commission]] in Germany.}}\n\nThis is how the British ceded the [[Saarland(Land)|Saarland]], the [[Rhineland Palatinate|Palatinate]] and the territories on the left bank of the [[Rhine]] until [[Remagen]] including [[Trier (Germany)|Trier]], [[Koblenz]] and [[Montabaur]]. While the Americans ceded the South of [[Baden Baden]] (which became [[Baden (Land)|Land of Baden]])), the South of [[People's Free State of W\u00fcrttemberg]] (which became Land of [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]]), [[District of Lindau|Lindau circle]] on [[Lake Constance]] and four circles of [[Hesse (Land)|Hesse]] on the shore right of the Rhine.<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />\n\n[[French forces in Germany]] officially took possession of their area on July 26, 1945.<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />\n\nIn April and May 1945, the [[1st Army (France)|French 1st Army]] had captured [[Karlsruhe]] and [[Stuttgart]], and conquered a territory extending to [[Berghof (residence)|Hitler's Eagle's Nest]] and the westernmost part of Austria. In July, the French relinquished Stuttgart to the Americans, and in exchange were given control over cities west of the Rhine such as [[Mainz]] and [[Koblenz]].<ref>{{cite book |last=de Gaulle|first= Charles|title= M\u00e9moires de guerre : Le Salut 1944-1946|year=1959 |publisher=Plon|pages=170, 207}}</ref> All this resulted in two barely contiguous areas of Germany along the French border which met at just a single point along the River [[Rhine]]. Three German states (''[[States of Germany|Land]]'') were established: [[Rheinland Pfalz]] in the North and West and on the other hand [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]] and [[South Baden]], who later formed [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] together with ''W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden'' of the American Zone.\n\nThe French Zone of Occupation included the [[Saar Protectorate]], which was disentangled from it on 16 February 1946. By 18 December 1946 customs controls were established between the Saar area and Allied-occupied Germany. The French zone ceded further areas adjacent to the Saar (in mid-1946, early 1947, and early 1949).{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIncluded in the French zone was the town of [[B\u00fcsingen am Hochrhein]], a German exclave separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of neutral [[Switzerland|Swiss]] territory. The Swiss government agreed to allow limited numbers of French troops to pass through its territory in order to maintain law and order in B\u00fcsingen.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIt was not until August 12, 1945, that two Berlin districts ([[Reinickendorf]] and [[Wedding | Wedding District]]) were assigned to them.<ref name = \"GMFB\">{{cite web| url=http://ekladata.com/HsfUaqdi31GzolZtcyCvSXKbYcs/GMFB.pdf| format = Pdf\n| title = French Military Government of Berlin| author =| publisher =| year =| access-date = July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Fotothek df pk 0000178 036.jpg|[[Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin|French forces]] in front of the [[Brandenburg Gate]] in Berlin, 1946\nFile:Insigne-Forces-Fran\u00e7aises-Berlin.jpg|Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin (French Forces in Berlin) insignia after 1949\n</gallery>\n\nAt the end of October 1946, the French Zone had a population of:\n* Rheinland Pfalz 2.7 million\n* Baden (South Baden) 1.2 million\n* W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern 1.05 million\n(The Saar Protectorate had a further 0.8 million.)<ref name=\"digizeitschriften.de\">[http://www.digizeitschriften.de/dms/img/?PID=PPN514402342_1952%7Clog10 \"I. Gebiet und Bev\u00f6lkerung\"]. [[Statistisches Bundesamt]]. Wiesbaden.</ref>\n\nA [[French Education Directorate in Germany]] was created immediately to allow schooling for children of military and civilian families.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Monnet plan]]\n* [[Allied-occupied Austria]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[:de:Corine Defrance|Corine Defrance]], ''La Politique culturelle de la France sur la rive gauche du Rhin'', 1945\u20131955, [[Presses universitaires de Strasbourg]], 1994.\n* ''Compte rendu du deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s de l'Organisation des fonctionnaires r\u00e9sistants en Allemagne'', H\u00f6llhof, 1949\n*Hillel, Marc, ''L'occupation fran\u00e7aise en Allemagne 1945-1949'', Balland, 1983.\n\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Germany]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Germany| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1945]]\n[[Category:French military occupations]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Germany relations]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''[[France|French]] occupation zone''' (in [[German language|German]]: ''Franz\u00f6sische Besatzungszone''), was one of the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied areas]] established in [[Germany]] after [[World War II]].\n\nFollowing the [[Armistice of the First World War]], [[Allies of the First World War |Allied]] forces occupied part of German territory until the [[1920s]] and France administered the [[Territory of the Saar Basin]] until 1935.\n\nThe strength of the occupying forces was 100,000 in the Rhine territories in the calmest periods. The maximum of soldiers was reached in May 1921 during the first occupation of [[Ruhrort]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]] with {{formatnum: 250000}} soldiers including {{formatnum: 210000}} French.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}[http://rha.revues.org/index6333.html Occupy Germany after 1918], ''[[Historical review of the armies]],'' 2009.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAt the end of the [[Second World War]], before the [[Yalta conference]] (4-11 February 1945), no occupation zone in Germany was to be allocated to France. At the insistence of [[Charles de Gaulle]] and [[Provisional Government of the French Republic]], [[Winston Churchill | Churchill]] obtained from [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] that an occupation zone was to be allocated to France provided that this consists of zones previously occupied by the Americans and the British <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\">\n{{web link\n| url = http://docnum.univ-lorraine.fr/public/UPV-M/Theses/1994/Perrein_Engels.Helene.LMZ9412_1.pdf\n| format = Pdf\n| titre = The military presence in Germany from 1945 to 1993\n| author = H. Pennein-Engels\n| publisher = University of Metz - Faculty of Letters and Human Sciences\n| year = 1994\n| accessed on = July 8, 2015\n}}.</ref>:\n\n; Extract from the final press release, Article 4:\n{{block quote | IV. Occupation zone for France and control council in Germany <br />\nIt was decided that an area of \u200b\u200bGermany would be allocated to France to be occupied by French forces. This zone would be taken from the British and American zones and its extent would be fixed by the British and the Americans, in agreement with the French Provisional Government.\n\nIt was also decided that the French Provisional Government would be invited to be part of the [[Allied Control Council|Allied Control Commission]] in Germany.}}\n\nThis is how the British ceded the [[Saarland(Land)|Saarland]], the [[Rhineland Palatinate|Palatinate]] and the territories on the left bank of the [[Rhine]] until [[Remagen]] including [[Trier (Germany) | Trier]], [[Koblenz]] and [[Montabaur]]. While the Americans ceded the South of [[Baden Baden]] (which became [[Baden (Land) | Land of Baden]])), the South of [[People's Free State of W\u00fcrttemberg]] (which became Land of [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]]), [[District of Lindau | Lindau circle]] on [[Lake Constance]] and four circles of [[Hesse (Land) | Hesse]] on the shore right of the Rhine <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />.\n\n[[French forces in Germany]] officially took possession of their area on July 26, 1945.<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />\n\nIn April and May 1945, the [[1st Army (France)|French 1st Army]] had captured [[Karlsruhe]] and [[Stuttgart]], and conquered a territory extending to [[Berghof (residence)|Hitler's Eagle's Nest]] and the westernmost part of Austria. In July, the French relinquished Stuttgart to the Americans, and in exchange were given control over cities west of the Rhine such as [[Mainz]] and [[Koblenz]].<ref>{{cite book |last=de Gaulle|first= Charles|title= M\u00e9moires de guerre : Le Salut 1944-1946|year=1959 |publisher=Plon|pages=170, 207}}</ref> All this resulted in two barely contiguous areas of Germany along the French border which met at just a single point along the River [[Rhine]]. Three German states (''[[States of Germany|Land]]'') were established: [[Rheinland Pfalz]] in the North and West and on the other hand [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]] and [[South Baden]], who later formed [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] together with ''W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden'' of the American Zone.\n\nThe French Zone of Occupation included the [[Saar Protectorate]], which was disentangled from it on 16 February 1946. By 18 December 1946 customs controls were established between the Saar area and Allied-occupied Germany. The French zone ceded further areas adjacent to the Saar (in mid-1946, early 1947, and early 1949).{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIncluded in the French zone was the town of [[B\u00fcsingen am Hochrhein]], a German exclave separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of neutral [[Switzerland|Swiss]] territory. The Swiss government agreed to allow limited numbers of French troops to pass through its territory in order to maintain law and order in B\u00fcsingen.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIt was not until August 12, 1945, that two Berlin districts ([[Reinickendorf | Reinickendorf]] and [[Wedding | Wedding District]]) were assigned to them.<ref name = \"GMFB\">{{cite web| url=http://ekladata.com/HsfUaqdi31GzolZtcyCvSXKbYcs/GMFB.pdf| format = Pdf\n| title = French Military Government of Berlin| author =| publisher =| year =| access-date = July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Fotothek df pk 0000178 036.jpg|[[Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin|French forces]] in front of the [[Brandenburg Gate]] in Berlin, 1946\nFile:Insigne-Forces-Fran\u00e7aises-Berlin.jpg|Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin (French Forces in Berlin) insignia after 1949\n</gallery>\n\nAt the end of October 1946, the French Zone had a population of:\n* Rheinland Pfalz 2.7 million\n* Baden (South Baden) 1.2 million\n* W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern 1.05 million\n(The Saar Protectorate had a further 0.8 million.)<ref name=\"digizeitschriften.de\">[http://www.digizeitschriften.de/dms/img/?PID=PPN514402342_1952%7Clog10 \"I. Gebiet und Bev\u00f6lkerung\"]. [[Statistisches Bundesamt]]. Wiesbaden.</ref>\n\nA [[French Education Directorate in Germany]] was created immediately to allow schooling for children of military and civilian families.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Monnet plan]]\n* [[Allied-occupied Austria]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[:de:Corine Defrance|Corine Defrance]], ''La Politique culturelle de la France sur la rive gauche du Rhin'', 1945-1955, [[Presses universitaires de Strasbourg]], 1994.\n* ''Compte rendu du deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s de l'Organisation des fonctionnaires r\u00e9sistants en Allemagne'', H\u00f6llhof, 1949\n*Hillel, Marc, ''L'occupation fran\u00e7aise en Allemagne 1945-1949'', Balland, 1983.\n\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Germany]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Germany| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1945]]\n[[Category:French military occupations]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Germany relations]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1945-1955 \u2192 1945\u20131955", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_occupation_zone_in_Germany"}
{"title_page": "South African College Schools", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = South African College Schools (SACS)\n|image             = \n|imagesize         =\n|caption           = Badge of the South African College Schools, based on the original South African College badge, which was replaced by the badges of the South African College Schools and the University of Cape Town.\n|location          =Newlands\n|streetaddress     = Newlands Avenue (High School)<br />Dean Street (Junior School)\n|region            =[[Southern Suburbs]]\n|city              = [[Cape Town]]\n|province          = [[Western Cape]]\n|postalcode        = 7700\n|country           = [[South Africa]]\n|country1          =\n|coordinates       =\n|schoolnumber      =\n|schoolboard       =\n|district          =\n|authority         =\n|religion          =\n|denomination      =\n|oversight         =\n|affiliation       =\n|superintendent    =\n|trustee           =\n|founder           =\n|specialist        =\n|president         =\n|head_label        = Headmaster\n|head              = Brendan Grant (High School) <br /> Fran\u00e7ois Nel (Junior School)\n|principal         =\n|viceprincipal     =\n|staff             =\n|ranking           =\n|faculty           =\n|teaching_staff    =\n|roll              =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classes           =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|houses            = High School: <br/> Baxter <br /> Rosedale <br /> Russel <br /> Shaw <br /> <hr> Junior School: <Br /> Hofmeyr <br /> Kipps <br /> Lewis <br /> van Holdt\n|schooltype        =\n|fundingtype       =\n|system            =\n|fees              =\n|tuition           = Grade 8 R40,700 Grade 9\u201312 R38,900 (High School) <br /> R 35 500 (Junior School)\n|revenue           =\n|endowment         =\n|budget            =\n|products          =\n|grades            = R-12\n|age range         =\n|medium            =\n|language          = English (primary)\n|classrooms        =\n|campus            =\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|song              = [[#The S.A.C.|The S.A.C.]]\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''[[Spectemur agendo]]''\n|motto_translation = Let us be judged by our deeds\n|accreditation     = [[Matriculation (South Africa)|Senior Certificate]], [[GCE Advanced Level|GCE A-levels]]\n|rival             =\n|mascot            =\n|mascot image      =\n|sports            =\n|patron            =\n|team_name         =\n|nickname          =\n|school_colours    = White, sky blue, navy blue\n|school_colors     =\n|yearbook          =\n|publication       =\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1 October 1829\n|status            =\n|closed            =\n|students          =\n|pupils            =\n|alumni            =\n|nobel_laureates   =\n|enrollment        = 780 (High School) <br /> 650 (Junior School)\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|homepage          ={{url|sacollege.org.za}}\n}}\n\nThe '''South African College Schools''' is a [[State school|Semi-private]] [[English language|English medium]] primary and secondary education institution in the suburb of  [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]] in [[Cape Town]] in the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]]. Founded in 1829,<ref>{{cite book|author=Everhardus Cornelis Gode Molsbergen|title=A History of South Africa for Use in Schools|year=2009|publisher=BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009|page=186}}</ref> it is the oldest school in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sacshigh.org.za/|title=SACS High School}}</ref> SACS is one of four schools expressly named by [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]] to offer an annual [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to one of its graduating students.<ref name=\"CJR1902\">{{cite web | last = Rhodes  | first = Cecil John | title = Will and Condicils of the Rt Hon. Cecil John Rhodes. | url = http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/files/governancedocs/WillandCodicils.pdf | publisher= Rhodes Trust, University Press Oxford | format=PDF | page=10 }}</ref> The schools are a combination of the South African College Junior School and the South African College High School.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Original SA College Schools Building.jpg|thumb|left|Rosedale House]]\n[[File:Detail of SACS sign above door.jpg|thumb|left|SACS Badge]]\nThe concept of the '''[[South African College]]''' was first formed in 1791 when the Dutch Commissioner-General, [[Jacob Abraham de Mist|Jacob Abraham Uitenhage de Mist]], asked for funding to be set aside to improve schooling in the Cape. After the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] took over control of the [[Cape Colony]] the second colonial governor, [[Lord Charles Somerset|Lord Charles Henry Somerset]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}}, gave permission for the funds reserved by de Mist to be used to establish the South African College in 1814.\n\nThe founding committee met in the [[Groote Kerk, Cape Town|Groote Kerk]] to discuss funding and accommodation for the school and on 1 October 1829, the inauguration of the South African College was held and classes began. The original location of the school was in the ''Weeshuis'' on Long Street and moved to what is now known as the ''Egyptian Building'' in the Gardens district of Cape Town in 1841.\n\nIt was decided in 1874 that the younger students should be separated from their older counterparts. The South African College was separated into the ''College'' which became the [[University of Cape Town]] and the ''College School''.<ref>{{cite book|title=\tStandard encyclopaedia of Southern Africa, Volume 10|publisher=NASOU|year=1976|page=96}}</ref>\n\nThe College School moved to its own building on Orange Street, separate from the College, in 1896. For the next few decades, the school grew and the building became too small for the number of students attending.\n\nIn 1959 the school moved to its current home in the Montebello Estate in Newlands,<ref>{{cite book|title=Cape Town, city of good hope|last=Honikman|first=A. H.|publisher=H. B. Timmins|year=1966|page=63}}</ref> former home of the mining magnate [[Max Michaelis|Sir Max Michaelis]], after a decade-long negotiation with the Cape Administration.\n\nIn 2012, the school grounds were used to film Spud 2: The Madness Continues. \n\n{{Coord|33|58|13.45|S|18|27|36.38|E|display=title}}\n\n==School buildings==\nThe current school buildings are situated along Dean Street and Newlands Avenue in Cape Town.\n\nThe Junior School is located along Dean Street and is equipped with numerous fields for sporting activities, of which some are shared with the High School. The Junior School has a full length swimming pool with a smaller children's pool for the younger students. A number of [[tennis]] courts are also available to the students. The Junior School has a new Media Centre which hosts computer facilities, a new library and classrooms. The music department also has its own [[auditorium]] for cultural events and is also used for events with smaller audiences. The Junior School's [[boarding house]] is named after ''J E De Villiers''.\n\nThe High School is closest to Newlands Avenue which also hosts a number of sport fields for the various sports which the school offers throughout the year. The swimming pool is mainly used for [[Water Polo]] and is also heated to facilitate training and usage in winter. The High School also recently had a new Media Centre constructed with air-conditioned computer labs and library. The school hall is named after one of its most famous students, [[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]]. The boarding houses for the High School are the ''Michaelis House'' (for the junior students) and ''Rosedale House'' (for the senior students).\n\n== High School Sport ==\nSACS offers a wide variety of summer and winter sports for boys to partake in during the year. Boys are made to partake in at least one main summer and winter sport and may also partake in other secondar sports, provided they are involved in a main sport first.\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'''Main summer sports'''\n** [[Cricket]]\n** Swimming\n** [[Water polo|Waterpolo]]\n** [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n** [[Tennis]]\n** [[Basketball]]\n** [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n*'''Secondary summer sports'''\n** [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]]\n**[[Road cycling]]\n*'''Main winter sports'''\n** [[Rugby union]]\n** [[Rugby union|Hocke]] [[Field hockey|y]]\n** [[Cross country running|Cross-country]]\n** [[Squash (sport)|Squash]]\n** [[Mountain biking]]\n*'''Secondary winter sports'''\n** [[Bodyboarding]]\n** [[Golf]]\n** [[Surfing]]\n** [[Shooting sport|Shooting]] (Currently Inactive)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== High school clubs and societies  ==\nCulture plays a large role in the SACS High School community. Many clubs, societies and bands are situated within the high school and are largely run and coordinated by the boys, with each club or society being supervised by a teacher. As of 2016, there were active clubs, societies and bands operating within SACS. These are the: \n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* History Society\n* Marimba Band\n* Debating Society\n* SACS Choir\n* SACS Big Band\n* SACS Junior Jazz Band\n* SACS Concert and Marching bands\n* SACS Clarinet Ensemble \n* SACS Flute Ensemble \n* SACS Brass Ensemble \n* SACS Saxophone Ensemble \n* Muslim Students' Association\n* Christian Union\n* Science Club\n* RCL\n* Interact Club\n* Photography Society\n* First Aid Society\n* Multimedia Society\n* Film Society\n* Chess Club\n* Waterpolo Table Officials\n* Afrikaans Society \n* Mountain Club\n* French Club\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Uniform==\nThe traditional school colour of navy blue was determined in the 1880s when SACS pupils purchased the only pattern available of alternating white, light- and dark-blue horizontal stripes from ''Porter Hodgson's Outfitters'' in Cape Town. Prior to this, the pupils wore what they could afford while still being presentable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=342&fArticleId=2516444|title=School uniforms \u2013 what purpose do they serve?|date=11 May 2005|first=Fouzia|last=van der Fort}}</ref>\n\nToday the High School uniform consists of a summer and winter uniform. During summer, boys wear khaki shorts with long khaki socks and brown shoes. In winter the basic uniform consists of long charcoal pants, black socks and black shoes. Both the summer and winter uniforms are accompanied by the SACS navy-blue blazer, white school shirt and school tie. Both these uniforms can be worn at any time during the school year, except for certain formal school functions where a certain uniform is required.\n\nThe Junior School uniform consists of a white shirt, charcoal shorts, a SACS Junior belt, charcoal socks with thin light and dark blue stripes at the top, black shoes and the Junior School tie, which is similar to the High School tie, apart from one minor difference. The Junior School uniform includes the same blazer as the High School, with the exception of the Junior School not modifying blazers for Blues (colours) awards, as is practised by the high school.\n\n==Rhodes Scholarship==\nWhen [[Cecil John Rhodes]] died in 1902, he specifically named the South African College in his will as one of four schools in the [[Cape Colony]] where the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] would be awarded on an annual basis for a former student to study at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za/about.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships in Southern Africa|date=3 January 2009|first=Tim|last=Nuttall}}</ref>\n\n==Old Boys' Union==\n===Old Boys===\n[[File:The leader and his deputy, jan smuts on the right and jan hofmeyr on the left.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr and former Prime Minister of South Africa, [[Jan Smuts]]]]\n*Dr. [[Abdullah Abdurahman]] \u2013 Medical Doctor, Cape Muslim leader & founder of the anti-apartheid movement, African People's Organisation and human rights campaigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/dr-abdullah-abdurahman|title=Dr. Abdullah Abdurahman|last=sahoboss|date=17 February 2011|website=South African History Online}}</ref>\n*Captain [[Andrew Beauchamp-Proctor]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC and bar]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]]\n*[[Kyle Brown (rugby union)|Kyle Brown]] \u2013 [[South Africa national rugby sevens team|South Africa Sevens]] captain 2008\u2013present and [[Olympic Games]] medalist Rio 2016.\n*[[Abraham Fischer]] \u2013 Sole Prime Minister of the Orange River Colony in South Africa<ref>Clingman, Stephen (1998). Bram Fischer: Afrikaner revolutionary. David Philip Publishers. p. 8. {{ISBN|0-86486-677-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]] \u2014 former Deputy Prime Minister of South Africa, Minister of Finance and Education, Administrator of the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodes Scholar]]\n*[[Leonard Hoffmann, Baron Hoffmann]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}} \u2014 former senior British justice\n*[[Peter Kirsten]] \u2014 former [[South African cricket team|South African]] cricketer\n*[[Dylan Lewis]]- South African sculptor and artist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dylanlewis.co.za/about/bio.php|title=Dylan Lewis \u2013 Biography|website=dylanlewis.co.za}}</ref>\n*[[Gino Lupini]] \u2013 [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy Seven]] Rugby 2016\u2013present.\n*[[Nicolaas Petrus van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 [[Afrikaans]]-language poet, playwright, and scholar\n*[[W. E. G. Louw|William Ewart Gladstone van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 Afrikaans-language poet\n*[[Percy Montgomery|Percival Colin \"Percy\" Montgomery]] \u2014 former [[South Africa national rugby union team|South African]] [[rugby union]] footballer, [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] winner & the first Springbok to earn 100 caps.\n*Dr. [[Cecil Moss]] \u2014 former South African rugby union player and South African Rugby Union coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugby15.co.za/rip-dr-cecil-moss-1925-2017/|title=RIP Dr Cecil Moss, 1925\u20132017 \u2013 15.co.za \u2013 - Rugby News, Live Scores, Results, Fixtures|website=rugby15.co.za}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Allan Mossop]], Chief Judge of the [[British Supreme Court for China]]\n*[[Sebastien Rousseau]] \u2013 Three time Olympian Swimmer for South Africa, Commonwealth Games Medalist, South African Record Holder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridagators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3493|title=Sebastien Rousseau \u2013 Men's Swimming & Diving|website=Florida Gators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sascoc.co.za/2009/04/14/rousseau-leads-the-charge/|title=Record for Rousseau|date=14 April 2009|website=sascoc.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/65499|title=Sebastien Rousseau|website=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref>\n*[[Albie Sachs]] \u2014 former justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Sachs|first=Albie|title=Advancing human rights in South Africa|page=iii|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1992}}</ref>\n*[[Ryan Sandes]] \u2013 ultramarathon trail runner who has won all four of the [[4 Deserts]] races, amongst other achievements.\n*[[Stephen Simpson]] \u2014 race car driver and former [[A1 Team South Africa|A1 Grand Prix Team South Africa]] driver\n*[[Ross Skeate]] \u2014 rugby union footballer for [[RC Toulonnais|RC Toulon]] and formerly for [[Stormers]] and [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] rugby union teams[[File:Percy Montgomery.JPG|right|thumb|Percy Montgomery]]\n*[[Simon Walker (business)|Simon Walker]] \u2014 British business executive, government advisor and Director General of the UK's [[Institute of Directors]]\n*[[Eric Lloyd Williams]] \u2014 journalist and [[World War II]] correspondent\n*[[Solly Zuckerman, Baron Zuckerman]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]}} \u2014 British zoologist, public servant and key World War II [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] strategic advisor\n* [[Benjamin Duff]] Springbok rugby player\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Saasveld Forestry College]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{cite book|url=|title=SACS 175 \u2013 A Celebration|last=Veitch|first=Neil|publisher=SACS 175 Book Committee|year=2002|isbn=|location=Cape Town|pages=260|doi=|id=|authorlink=|author2=}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sacollege.org.za/ South African College Schools Website]\n*[http://www.sacsjunior.org.za/ SACS Junior School]\n*[http://www.sacsrugby.com/ SACS Rugby Site]\n{{CapeTownSchools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1829]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:Newlands, Cape Town]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = South African College Schools (SACS)\n|image             = \n|imagesize         =\n|caption           = Badge of the South African College Schools, based on the original South African College badge, which was replaced by the badges of the South African College Schools and the University of Cape Town.\n|location          =Newlands\n|streetaddress     = Newlands Avenue (High School)<br />Dean Street (Junior School)\n|region            =[[Southern Suburbs]]\n|city              = [[Cape Town]]\n|province          = [[Western Cape]]\n|postalcode        = 7700\n|country           = [[South Africa]]\n|country1          =\n|coordinates       =\n|schoolnumber      =\n|schoolboard       =\n|district          =\n|authority         =\n|religion          =\n|denomination      =\n|oversight         =\n|affiliation       =\n|superintendent    =\n|trustee           =\n|founder           =\n|specialist        =\n|president         =\n|head_label        = Headmaster\n|head              = Brendan Grant (High School) <br /> Fran\u00e7ois Nel (Junior School)\n|principal         =\n|viceprincipal     =\n|staff             =\n|ranking           =\n|faculty           =\n|teaching_staff    =\n|roll              =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classes           =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|houses            = High School: <br/> Baxter <br /> Rosedale <br /> Russel <br /> Shaw <br /> <hr> Junior School: <Br /> Hofmeyr <br /> Kipps <br /> Lewis <br /> van Holdt\n|schooltype        =\n|fundingtype       =\n|system            =\n|fees              =\n|tuition           = Grade 8 R40,700 Grade 9\u201312 R38,900 (High School) <br /> R 35 500 (Junior School)\n|revenue           =\n|endowment         =\n|budget            =\n|products          =\n|grades            = R-12\n|age range         =\n|medium            =\n|language          = English (primary)\n|classrooms        =\n|campus            =\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|song              = [[#The S.A.C.|The S.A.C.]]\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''[[Spectemur agendo]]''\n|motto_translation = Let us be judged by our deeds\n|accreditation     = [[Matriculation (South Africa)|Senior Certificate]], [[GCE Advanced Level|GCE A-levels]]\n|rival             =\n|mascot            =\n|mascot image      =\n|sports            =\n|patron            =\n|team_name         =\n|nickname          =\n|school_colours    = White, sky blue, navy blue\n|school_colors     =\n|yearbook          =\n|publication       =\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1 October 1829\n|status            =\n|closed            =\n|students          =\n|pupils            =\n|alumni            =\n|nobel_laureates   =\n|enrollment        = 780 (High School) <br /> 650 (Junior School)\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|homepage          ={{url|sacollege.org.za}}\n}}\n\nThe '''South African College Schools''' is a [[State school|Semi-private]] [[English language|English medium]] primary and secondary education institution in the suburb of  [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]] in [[Cape Town]] in the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]]. Founded in 1829,<ref>{{cite book|author=Everhardus Cornelis Gode Molsbergen|title=A History of South Africa for Use in Schools|year=2009|publisher=BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009|page=186}}</ref> it is the nineteenth oldest school in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.parent24.com/Learn/Primary-school/this-list-with-200-of-south-africas-oldest-schools-may-surprise-you-20180409|title=This list with 200 of South Africa's oldest schools may surprise you|date=9 April 2018|website=Parent|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref> SACS is one of four schools expressly named by [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]] to offer an annual [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to one of its graduating students.<ref name=\"CJR1902\">{{cite web | last = Rhodes  | first = Cecil John | title = Will and Condicils of the Rt Hon. Cecil John Rhodes. | url = http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/files/governancedocs/WillandCodicils.pdf | publisher= Rhodes Trust, University Press Oxford | format=PDF | page=10 }}</ref> The schools are a combination of the South African College Junior School and the South African College High School.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Original SA College Schools Building.jpg|thumb|left|Rosedale House]]\n[[File:Detail of SACS sign above door.jpg|thumb|left|SACS Badge]]\nThe concept of the '''[[South African College]]''' was first formed in 1791 when the Dutch Commissioner-General, [[Jacob Abraham de Mist|Jacob Abraham Uitenhage de Mist]], asked for funding to be set aside to improve schooling in the Cape. After the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] took over control of the [[Cape Colony]] the second colonial governor, [[Lord Charles Somerset|Lord Charles Henry Somerset]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}}, gave permission for the funds reserved by de Mist to be used to establish the South African College in 1814.\n\nThe founding committee met in the [[Groote Kerk, Cape Town|Groote Kerk]] to discuss funding and accommodation for the school and on 1 October 1829, the inauguration of the South African College was held and classes began. The original location of the school was in the ''Weeshuis'' on Long Street and moved to what is now known as the ''Egyptian Building'' in the Gardens district of Cape Town in 1841.\n\nIt was decided in 1874 that the younger students should be separated from their older counterparts. The South African College was separated into the ''College'' which became the [[University of Cape Town]] and the ''College School''.<ref>{{cite book|title=\tStandard encyclopaedia of Southern Africa, Volume 10|publisher=NASOU|year=1976|page=96}}</ref>\n\nThe College School moved to its own building on Orange Street, separate from the College, in 1896. For the next few decades, the school grew and the building became too small for the number of students attending.\n\nIn 1959 the school moved to its current home in the Montebello Estate in Newlands,<ref>{{cite book|title=Cape Town, city of good hope|last=Honikman|first=A. H.|publisher=H. B. Timmins|year=1966|page=63}}</ref> former home of the mining magnate [[Max Michaelis|Sir Max Michaelis]], after a decade-long negotiation with the Cape Administration.\n\nIn 2012, the school grounds were used to film Spud 2: The Madness Continues. \n\n{{Coord|33|58|13.45|S|18|27|36.38|E|display=title}}\n\n==School buildings==\nThe current school buildings are situated along Dean Street and Newlands Avenue in Cape Town.\n\nThe Junior School is located along Dean Street and is equipped with numerous fields for sporting activities, of which some are shared with the High School. The Junior School has a full length swimming pool with a smaller children's pool for the younger students. A number of [[tennis]] courts are also available to the students. The Junior School has a new Media Centre which hosts computer facilities, a new library and classrooms. The music department also has its own [[auditorium]] for cultural events and is also used for events with smaller audiences. The Junior School's [[boarding house]] is named after ''J E De Villiers''.\n\nThe High School is closest to Newlands Avenue which also hosts a number of sport fields for the various sports which the school offers throughout the year. The swimming pool is mainly used for [[Water Polo]] and is also heated to facilitate training and usage in winter. The High School also recently had a new Media Centre constructed with air-conditioned computer labs and library. The school hall is named after one of its most famous students, [[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]]. The boarding houses for the High School are the ''Michaelis House'' (for the junior students) and ''Rosedale House'' (for the senior students).\n\n== High School Sport ==\nSACS offers a wide variety of summer and winter sports for boys to partake in during the year. Boys are made to partake in at least one main summer and winter sport and may also partake in other secondar sports, provided they are involved in a main sport first.\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'''Main summer sports'''\n** [[Cricket]]\n** Swimming\n** [[Water polo|Waterpolo]]\n** [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n** [[Tennis]]\n** [[Basketball]]\n** [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n*'''Secondary summer sports'''\n** [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]]\n**[[Road cycling]]\n*'''Main winter sports'''\n** [[Rugby union]]\n** [[Rugby union|Hocke]] [[Field hockey|y]]\n** [[Cross country running|Cross-country]]\n** [[Squash (sport)|Squash]]\n** [[Mountain biking]]\n*'''Secondary winter sports'''\n** [[Bodyboarding]]\n** [[Golf]]\n** [[Surfing]]\n** [[Shooting sport|Shooting]] (Currently Inactive)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== High school clubs and societies  ==\nCulture plays a large role in the SACS High School community. Many clubs, societies and bands are situated within the high school and are largely run and coordinated by the boys, with each club or society being supervised by a teacher. As of 2016, there were active clubs, societies and bands operating within SACS. These are the: \n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* History Society\n* Marimba Band\n* Debating Society\n* SACS Choir\n* SACS Big Band\n* SACS Junior Jazz Band\n* SACS Concert and Marching bands\n* SACS Clarinet Ensemble \n* SACS Flute Ensemble \n* SACS Brass Ensemble \n* SACS Saxophone Ensemble \n* Muslim Students' Association\n* Christian Union\n* Science Club\n* RCL\n* Interact Club\n* Photography Society\n* First Aid Society\n* Multimedia Society\n* Film Society\n* Chess Club\n* Waterpolo Table Officials\n* Afrikaans Society \n* Mountain Club\n* French Club\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Uniform==\nThe traditional school colour of navy blue was determined in the 1880s when SACS pupils purchased the only pattern available of alternating white, light- and dark-blue horizontal stripes from ''Porter Hodgson's Outfitters'' in Cape Town. Prior to this, the pupils wore what they could afford while still being presentable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=342&fArticleId=2516444|title=School uniforms \u2013 what purpose do they serve?|date=11 May 2005|first=Fouzia|last=van der Fort}}</ref>\n\nToday the High School uniform consists of a summer and winter uniform. During summer, boys wear khaki shorts with long khaki socks and brown shoes. In winter the basic uniform consists of long charcoal pants, black socks and black shoes. Both the summer and winter uniforms are accompanied by the SACS navy-blue blazer, white school shirt and school tie. Both these uniforms can be worn at any time during the school year, except for certain formal school functions where a certain uniform is required.\n\nThe Junior School uniform consists of a white shirt, charcoal shorts, a SACS Junior belt, charcoal socks with thin light and dark blue stripes at the top, black shoes and the Junior School tie, which is similar to the High School tie, apart from one minor difference. The Junior School uniform includes the same blazer as the High School, with the exception of the Junior School not modifying blazers for Blues (colours) awards, as is practised by the high school.\n\n==Rhodes Scholarship==\nWhen [[Cecil John Rhodes]] died in 1902, he specifically named the South African College in his will as one of four schools in the [[Cape Colony]] where the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] would be awarded on an annual basis for a former student to study at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za/about.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships in Southern Africa|date=3 January 2009|first=Tim|last=Nuttall}}</ref>\n\n==Old Boys' Union==\n===Old Boys===\n[[File:The leader and his deputy, jan smuts on the right and jan hofmeyr on the left.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr and former Prime Minister of South Africa, [[Jan Smuts]]]]\n*Dr. [[Abdullah Abdurahman]] \u2013 Medical Doctor, Cape Muslim leader & founder of the anti-apartheid movement, African People's Organisation and human rights campaigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/dr-abdullah-abdurahman|title=Dr. Abdullah Abdurahman|last=sahoboss|date=17 February 2011|website=South African History Online}}</ref>\n*Captain [[Andrew Beauchamp-Proctor]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC and bar]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]]\n*[[Kyle Brown (rugby union)|Kyle Brown]] \u2013 [[South Africa national rugby sevens team|South Africa Sevens]] captain 2008\u2013present and [[Olympic Games]] medalist Rio 2016.\n*[[Abraham Fischer]] \u2013 Sole Prime Minister of the Orange River Colony in South Africa<ref>Clingman, Stephen (1998). Bram Fischer: Afrikaner revolutionary. David Philip Publishers. p. 8. {{ISBN|0-86486-677-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]] \u2014 former Deputy Prime Minister of South Africa, Minister of Finance and Education, Administrator of the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodes Scholar]]\n*[[Leonard Hoffmann, Baron Hoffmann]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}} \u2014 former senior British justice\n*[[Peter Kirsten]] \u2014 former [[South African cricket team|South African]] cricketer\n*[[Dylan Lewis]]- South African sculptor and artist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dylanlewis.co.za/about/bio.php|title=Dylan Lewis \u2013 Biography|website=dylanlewis.co.za}}</ref>\n*[[Gino Lupini]] \u2013 [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy Seven]] Rugby 2016\u2013present.\n*[[Nicolaas Petrus van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 [[Afrikaans]]-language poet, playwright, and scholar\n*[[W. E. G. Louw|William Ewart Gladstone van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 Afrikaans-language poet\n*[[Percy Montgomery|Percival Colin \"Percy\" Montgomery]] \u2014 former [[South Africa national rugby union team|South African]] [[rugby union]] footballer, [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] winner & the first Springbok to earn 100 caps.\n*Dr. [[Cecil Moss]] \u2014 former South African rugby union player and South African Rugby Union coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugby15.co.za/rip-dr-cecil-moss-1925-2017/|title=RIP Dr Cecil Moss, 1925\u20132017 \u2013 15.co.za \u2013 - Rugby News, Live Scores, Results, Fixtures|website=rugby15.co.za}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Allan Mossop]], Chief Judge of the [[British Supreme Court for China]]\n*[[Sebastien Rousseau]] \u2013 Three time Olympian Swimmer for South Africa, Commonwealth Games Medalist, South African Record Holder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridagators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3493|title=Sebastien Rousseau \u2013 Men's Swimming & Diving|website=Florida Gators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sascoc.co.za/2009/04/14/rousseau-leads-the-charge/|title=Record for Rousseau|date=14 April 2009|website=sascoc.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/65499|title=Sebastien Rousseau|website=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref>\n*[[Albie Sachs]] \u2014 former justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Sachs|first=Albie|title=Advancing human rights in South Africa|page=iii|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1992}}</ref>\n*[[Ryan Sandes]] \u2013 ultramarathon trail runner who has won all four of the [[4 Deserts]] races, amongst other achievements.\n*[[Stephen Simpson]] \u2014 race car driver and former [[A1 Team South Africa|A1 Grand Prix Team South Africa]] driver\n*[[Ross Skeate]] \u2014 rugby union footballer for [[RC Toulonnais|RC Toulon]] and formerly for [[Stormers]] and [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] rugby union teams[[File:Percy Montgomery.JPG|right|thumb|Percy Montgomery]]\n*[[Simon Walker (business)|Simon Walker]] \u2014 British business executive, government advisor and Director General of the UK's [[Institute of Directors]]\n*[[Eric Lloyd Williams]] \u2014 journalist and [[World War II]] correspondent\n*[[Solly Zuckerman, Baron Zuckerman]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]}} \u2014 British zoologist, public servant and key World War II [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] strategic advisor\n* [[Benjamin Duff]] Springbok rugby player\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Saasveld Forestry College]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{cite book|url=|title=SACS 175 \u2013 A Celebration|last=Veitch|first=Neil|publisher=SACS 175 Book Committee|year=2002|isbn=|location=Cape Town|pages=260|doi=|id=|authorlink=|author2=}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sacollege.org.za/ South African College Schools Website]\n*[http://www.sacsjunior.org.za/ SACS Junior School]\n*[http://www.sacsrugby.com/ SACS Rugby Site]\n{{CapeTownSchools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1829]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:Newlands, Cape Town]]\n", "name_user": "Stevevandermerve", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_College_Schools"}
{"title_page": "PICRUSt", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = PICRUSt\n| title                  = \n| logo                   = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| logo caption           = \n| logo size              = \n| logo alt               = \n| screenshot             = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| caption                = \n| screenshot size        = \n| screenshot alt         = \n| collapsible            = \n| author                 = Morgan Langille,Jesse Zaneveld, Dan Knights, Joshua A Reyes, Jose C Clemente, Deron E Burkepile, Rebecca L Vega Thurber, [[Rob Knight (biologist)|Rob Knight]], Robert G Beiko, Curtis Huttenhower\n| developer              = Morgan Langille,Jesse Zaneveld,Daniel McDonald,Greg Caporaso,Gavin Douglas\n| released               = {{Start date and age|2013|07|29|df=yes/no}}\n| discontinued           = \n| latest release version = \n| latest release date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date    = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| status                 = \n| programming language   = Python, R\n| operating system       = \n| platform               = \n| size                   = \n| language               = \n| language count         = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote      = \n| genre                  = \n| license                = \n| alexa                  = \n| website               = {{URL|picrust.github.com/}}\n| standard               = \n| AsOf                   = \n}}\n\n'''PICRUSt'''<ref name=\"LangilleZaneveld2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Langille|first1=Morgan G I|last2=Zaneveld|first2=Jesse|last3=Caporaso|first3=J Gregory|last4=McDonald|first4=Daniel|last5=Knights|first5=Dan|last6=Reyes|first6=Joshua A|last7=Clemente|first7=Jose C|last8=Burkepile|first8=Deron E|last9=Vega Thurber|first9=Rebecca L|last10=Knight|first10=Rob|last11=Beiko|first11=Robert G|last12=Huttenhower|first12=Curtis|title=Predictive functional profiling of microbial communities using 16S rRNA marker gene sequences|journal=Nature Biotechnology|volume=31|issue=9|year=2013|pages=814\u2013821|issn=1087-0156|doi=10.1038/nbt.2676|pmid=23975157|pmc=3819121|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/12064405/3819121.pdf?sequence=1}}</ref>\nis a [[bioinformatics]] software package. The name is an abbreviation for ''Phylogenetic Investigation of Communities by Reconstruction of Unobserved States.''\n\nThe tool serves in the field of [[metagenomic]] analysis where it allows inference of the functional profile of a [[microbial]]\ncommunity based on [[marker gene]] survey along one or more samples. In essence, PICRUSt takes a user supplied [[operational taxonomic unit]] table (typically referred to as an OTU table), representing the marker gene sequences (most commonly a [[16S ribosomal RNA|16S]] [[Cluster analysis|cluster]]) accompanied with its relative abundance in each of the samples. The output of PICRUSt is a sample by functional-gene-count matrix, telling the count of each functional-gene in each of the samples surveyed. The ability of PICRUSt to estimate the functional-gene profile for a given sample relies on a set of known sequenced [[genomes]].  This could also be thought of as an automated alternative to manually researching the gene families likely to be present in organisms whose sequences are found in a [[16S ribosomal RNA]] [[amplicon library]]. The below description corresponds to the original version of PICRUSt, but a major update to this tool is currently being developed<ref name=\"Douglas et al., 2020\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1101/672295 | title=PICRUSt2: An improved and customizable approach for metagenome inference | journal=bioRxiv | year=2020 | last1=Douglas | first1=Gavin | last2=Maffei | first2=Vince | last3=Zaneveld | first3=Jesse | last4=Yurgel | first4=Svetlana | last5=Brown | first5=James | last6=Taylor | first6=Christopher | last7=Huttenhower | first7=Curtis | last8=Langille | first8=Morgan}}</ref>.\n\n==Genome prediction algorithm==\n\nIn an initial preprocessing phase, PICRUSt constructs [[confidence intervals]] and point predictions for the number of copies of each gene family in each bacterial and archaeal strain in a reference tree, using organisms with sequenced genomes as a reference. More specifically, for each gene family, PICRUSt maps known gene copy numbers (from complete sequenced genomes) onto a reference tree of life.  These gene family [[copy numbers]] are treated as [[continuous traits]], and an [[evolutionary model]] constructed under the assumption of [[Brownian Motion]]. These evolutionary models can be constructed with either [[Maximum Likelihood]], [[Relaxed Maximum Likelihood]] or [[Wagner Parsimony]]  This evolutionary model is then used to predict both a point estimate and a confidence interval for the copy number of microorganisms without sequenced genomes.  This 'genome prediction' step produces a large table of bacterial types (specifically [[operational taxonomic unit]] or OTUs) vs. gene family copy numbers. This table is distributed to end users. It is important to note that this prediction method is not the same as a nearest neighbor approach (i.e. just looking up the nearest sequenced genome), and was shown to give a small but significant improvement in accuracy over that strategy.  However, [[nearest neighbor search|nearest neighbor]] prediction is available as an option in PICRUSt.\n\nNotably, while this functionality is typically used for prediction of gene copy numbers in bacteria, it could, in principle, be used for prediction of any other [[continuous trait]] given trait data for diverse organisms and a reference [[phylogeny]].\n\nLangille et al<ref name=\"LangilleZaneveld2013\" /> tested the accuracy of this genome prediction step using leave-one-out cross validation on the input set of sequenced genomes.  Additional tests examined sensitivity to errors in [[phylogenetic inference]], [[lack of genomic data]], and the accuracy of the [[confidence intervals]] on gene content.\n\nA similar step predicts the copy number of [[16S rRNA]] genes.\n\n==Metagenome prediction algorithm==\n\nWhen applying PICRUSt to a [[16S rRNA]] gene library, PICRUSt matches reference [[operational taxonomic unit]]s against the tables, and retrieves a predicted 16S rRNA copy number and gene copy number for each gene family.  The abundance of each OTU is divided by its predicted copy number (if a bacterium has multiple 16S copies, its apparent abundance in 16S rRNA data will be inflated), and then multiplied by the copy number of the gene family.  This gives a prediction for the contribution of each OTU to the overall gene content of the sample (the [[metagenome]]). Finally, these individual contributions are summed together to produce an estimate of the genes present in the [[metagenome]].\n\nLangille et al., 2013<ref name=\"LangilleZaneveld2013\" /> tested the accuracy of this genome prediction step by using previously reported datasets in which the same biological sample was subjected to [[16S rRNA gene]] amplification and [[shotgun metagenomics]].  In these cases, the shotgun metagenomic results were taken as a representation of the 'true' community, and the 16S rRNA gene amplicon libraries fed into PICRUSt to attempt to predict those data. Test datasets included [[human microbiome]] samples from the [[Human Microbiome Project]], soil samples, diverse mammalian samples, and samples from the [[Guerrero Negro]] [[microbial mats]]\n\n==The Nearest Sequenced Taxon Index==\n\nBecause PICRUSt, and [[evolutionary comparative genomics]] in general, depends on sequenced genomes, biological samples from well-studied environments (many sequenced genomes) will be better predicted than poorly studied environments.  In order to assess how many genomes are available, PICRUSt optionally allows users to calculate a Nearest Sequenced Taxon Index (NSTI) for their samples.  This index reflects the average [[phylogenetic distance]] between each [[16S rRNA]] gene sequence in their sample, and a [[16S rRNA]] gene sequence from a fully [[sequenced genome]]. In general, the lower the NSTI score, the more accurate PICRUSt's predictions are expected to be. For example,<ref name=\"LangilleZaneveld2013\" /> showed that PICRUSt was much more accurate on diverse soil samples and samples from the [[Human Microbiome Project]] than on microbial mat samples from  [[Guerrero Negro]], which contained many bacteria without any sequenced relatives.\n\n==Related tools==\n\nOkuda et al., 2012<ref name=\"Okuda et al 2012\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/ncomms2203 |title=Okuda et al., 2012 | volume=3 | journal=Nature Communications |page=1203|year=2012 |last1=Okuda |first1=Shujiro |last2=Tsuchiya |first2=Yuki |last3=Kiriyama |first3=Chiho |last4=Itoh |first4=Masumi |last5=Morisaki |first5=Hisao |doi-access=free }}</ref> published a similar method that used a bounded k-Nearest Neighbor approach to predict virtual metagenomes. They validated their approach using [[16S rRNA]] gene sequences extracted from [[shotgun metagenomes]], and compared the predictions of their method against the full metagenome.\n\nCopyRighter,<ref name=\"Angly et al., 2015\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/2049-2618-2-11 | volume=2 | title=CopyRighter: a rapid tool for improving the accuracy of microbial community profiles through lineage-specific gene copy number correction | journal=Microbiome | page=11| year=2014 | last1=Angly | first1=Florent E | last2=Dennis | first2=Paul G | last3=Skarshewski | first3=Adam | last4=Vanwonterghem | first4=Inka | last5=Hugenholtz | first5=Philip | last6=Tyson | first6=Gene W | pmc=4021573 }}</ref> like PICRUSt, uses evolutionary modeling and  [[phylogenetic trait prediction]] to estimate [[16S rRNA]] gene sequence copy numbers for each bacterial and archaeal type in a sample, and then uses these estimates to correct estimates of community composition.\n\nPanFP<ref name=\"Jun et al., 2015\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/s13104-015-1462-8 | volume=8 | title=PanFP: pangenome-based functional profiles for microbial communities | journal=BMC Research Notes| year=2015 | last1=Jun | first1=Se-Ran | last2=Robeson | first2=Michael S. | last3=Hauser | first3=Loren J. | last4=Schadt | first4=Christopher W. | last5=Gorin | first5=Andrey A. | pmc=4584126 }}</ref> presented a similar method, but based on genome predictions for each taxonomic group.  Benchmarking showed highly similar performance to PICRUSt when compared on the same datasets. One advantage is that all OTUs, not just those in a reference phylogeny table can be used. One disadvantage is that confidence intervals and evolutionary models are not constructed.\n\nTax4Fun<ref name=\"A\u00dfhauer et al., 2015\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bioinformatics/btv287 | volume=31 | title=Tax4Fun: predicting functional profiles from metagenomic 16S rRNA data | journal=Bioinformatics | year=2015 | last1=A\u00dfhauer | first1=Kathrin | last2=Wemheuer | first2=Bernd | last3=Daniel | first3=Rolf | last4=Meinicke | first4=Peter | pmc= 4547618 }}</ref> is a similar tool based on linking the 16S ribosomal RNA genes from all [[KEGG]] organisms with 16S rRNA gene sequences found in the [[SILVA ribosomal RNA database]]. Originally this tool was restricted to 16S rRNA gene sequences found within the SILVA database. However, the latest version  of this tool, Tax4Fun2, can be used with OTUs or amplicon sequence variants from any clustering pipeline.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Metagenomics]]\n[[Category:Bioinformatics software]]\n[[Category:Environmental microbiology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=December 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = PICRUSt\n| title                  = \n| logo                   = <!-- Image name is enough -->\n| logo caption           = \n| logo size              = \n| logo alt               = \n| screenshot             = <