\u2013 Double Dixie  |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''1964 Live! In The Holiday Ballroom Chicago'' (Jazz Hour Compact Classics JH-1001, 1964 [1989])<ref name=\"64Holiday\">{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/1964-live%21-in-the-holiday-ballroom-chicago-mw0000263888 |title=Harry James And His Orchestra \u2013 Live! 1964 in the Holiday Ballroom, Chicago |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''One Night Stand With Harry James on Tour in '64'' (Joyce LP 1074, 1964 [1979])<ref name=\"64Tour\">{{cite web |url=http://encore.searchmobius.org/iii/encore/record/C__Rb13608018 |title=One night stand with Harry James on tour in '64: Midwest, October 1964 |publisher=Mobius |accessdate=February 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''New Versions of Down Beat Favorites'' (MGM SE-4265, 1965).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/new-version-of-down-beat-favorites-mw0000874347 |title= Harry James \u2013 New Versions Of Down Beat Favorites |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=February 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''In a Relaxed Mood'' (MGM SE-4274, 1965)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/in-a-relaxed-mood-mw0000896858 |title= Harry James \u2013 In A Relaxed Mood |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=March 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''Harry James Plays Green Onions & Other Great Hits'' ([[Dot Records|Dot]] DLP 3634 / DLP 25634, 1965)<ref>{{WorldCat|oclc=38000129|name=Harry James plays Green onions and other great hits}}</ref>\n* ''Harry James, Buddy Rich, Woody Herman '' (Europa Jazz EJ 1041, 1965 [1981])<ref name=\"BigBandLibraryLP\"/>\n* ''The Ballads and the Beat!'' (Dot DLP 3669 / DLP 25669, 1966)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-ballads-and-the-beat-mw0000876294 |title= Harry James \u2013 The Ballads and the Beat |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref>\n;Notes\n{{Notelist|group=ldr-std-alb}}\n\n'''With [[Charlie Parker]]'''\n* ''April in Paris: Charlie Parker with Strings'', [[Charlie Parker]] (1950)\n* ''[[Big Band (Charlie Parker album)|Big Band]]'' (Clef, 1954)\n\n'''With others'''\n* 1951 ''Lester Young Trio'', [[Lester Young]], [[Nat King Cole]] (not originally credited)\n* 1952 ''The Drum Battle'', [[Gene Krupa]]\n* 1954 ''Lionel Hampton Plays Love Songs'', [[Lionel Hampton]]\n* 1953 ''Sweets at the Haig'', [[Harry \"Sweets\" Edison]]\n* 1954 ''[[Little Jazz]]'', [[Roy Eldridge]] (Clef, 1954)\n* 1955 ''[[Pres and Sweets]]'', Lester Young and Harry Edison (Norgran, 1955)\n* 1955 ''Plays Count Basie'', [[Oscar Peterson]]\n* 1956 ''The Genius of Bud Powell'', [[Bud Powell]]\n* 1956 ''[[Ella and Louis]]'', [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Louis Armstrong]] (Verve, 1956)\n* 1958 ''Having Wonderful Time'', [[Tommy Dorsey]]\n* 1962 ''[[Burnin' Beat]]'', Gene Krupa\n* 1966 ''[[The Sounds of '66]]'', [[Sammy Davis Jr.]]\n* 1969 ''The Song Is You'', [[Stan Getz]]\n* 1974 ''Bunny Berigan: Leader & Sideman'', [[Bunny Berigan]]\n* 1982 ''[[Sinatra: World On a String]]'', [[Frank Sinatra]] (Universal, 1982 [2016])<ref name=\"AM cred\">{{cite web|title=Buddy Rich {{!}} Credits |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/buddy-rich-mn0000539774/credits |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=18 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Instruments==\nRich was known as a performer and endorser of [[Ludwig-Musser|Ludwig]], [[Slingerland]], and [[Rogers Drums|Rogers]] drums.<ref>Cohan, Jon. ''Star Sets: Drum Kits of the Great Drummers'', Hal Leonard Corporation. 1995, p. 23.</ref> While endorsing Slingerland in the '60s and '70s, Rich sometimes used a [[Fibes Drums|Fibes]] snare drum together with a Slingerland drum kit.<ref>Iero, Cheech. \"Buddy Rich: Revisited\", ''[[Modern Drummer]]'', December 1980 - January 1981.</ref> He switched exclusively to [[Ludwig-Musser|Ludwig]] in the late 1970s through the early 1980s. While recovering from a heart attack in 1983, Rich was presented with a 1940s-vintage Slingerland Radio King set, refurbished by Joe MacSweeney of Eames Drums,<ref>Cohan, Jon. ''Star Sets: Drum Kits of the Great Drummers'', Hal Leonard Corporation. 1995, p. 21.</ref> which he used until his death in 1987. Rich's typical setup included a 14\"\u00d724\" [[bass drum]], a 9\"\u00d713\" mounted [[Tom-tom drum|tom]], two 16\"\u00d716\" [[floor tom]]s (with the second tom usually serving as a towel holder), and a 5.5\"\u00d714\" [[snare drum]]. His [[cymbal]]s were typically [[Avedis Zildjian]]: 14\" New Beat [[hi-hat]]s, 20\" medium [[Ride cymbal|ride]], 8\" [[Splash cymbal|splash]], two 18\" [[Crash cymbal|crash]]es (thin and medium-thin).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zildjian.com/artists.html|title=Artists|website=Zildjian.com}}</ref> Sometimes a 6\" splash and later a 22\" [[Swish cymbal|swish]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://keepitlive.tripod.com/buddyrich/setup/setup.html|title=Buddy Rich's Setup|website=Keepitlive.tripod.com}}</ref> He also used [[Remo]] drumheads and Slingerland drumsticks.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.drummerworld.com/drummers/Buddy_Rich.html Buddy Rich on Drummerworld.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130705044047/http://en.wikiquote.org/wiki/Buddy_Rich Buddy Rich] at [[Wikiquote]]\n\n{{Buddy Rich|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rich, Buddy}}\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:American jazz drummers]]\n[[Category:American jazz singers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n[[Category:Bebop drummers]]\n[[Category:Big band bandleaders]]\n[[Category:Big band drummers]]\n[[Category:Mainstream jazz drummers]]\n[[Category:Swing drummers]]\n[[Category:Blue Note Records artists]]\n[[Category:EmArcy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Liberty Records artists]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records artists]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Deaths from brain tumor]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from California]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Jewish American jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jewish jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:United States Marines]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsburg, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Black Lion Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{lead too short|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|Jazz drummer and bandleader}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Buddy Rich \n| image               = Buddy Rich.jpg\n| caption             = Rich at the Arcadia Ballroom, New York City, May 1947\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       =  Bernard Rich\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1917|9|30|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|1987|4|2|1917|9|30|mf=yes}}\n| death_place       = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[big band]], [[Swing music|swing]]\n| occupation        = Musician and bandleader\n| instrument        = Drums\n| years_active     = 1921\u20131987\n| label                =[[Clef Records|Clef]], [[Norgran Records|Norgran]], [[Verve Records|Verve]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], [[Pacific Jazz Records|Pacific Jazz]], [[Liberty Records|Liberty]], [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], [[Groove Merchant]], [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], [[Mercury Records|Mercury]], [[MCA Records|MCA]], [[Argo Records|Argo]]\n| associated_acts = [[Joe Marsala]], [[Bunny Berigan]], [[Artie Shaw]], [[Tommy Dorsey]], [[Benny Carter]], [[Harry James]], [[Les Brown (bandleader)|Les Brown]], [[Frank Sinatra]], [[Charlie Ventura]], [[Jazz at the Philharmonic]], [[Nat King Cole]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]], [[Gene Krupa]], [[Louis Armstrong]], [[Neil Peart]]\n}}\n\n'''Bernard''' \"'''Buddy'''\" '''Rich''' (September 30, 1917 \u2013 April 2, 1987) was an American [[jazz]] drummer and bandleader. He is considered one of the most influential drummers of all time and was known for his virtuoso technique, power, and speed.<ref name=\"Yanow\">{{cite web |last1=Yanow |first1=Scott |title=Buddy Rich |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/buddy-rich-mn0000539774/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> He performed with [[Tommy Dorsey]], [[Harry James]] and [[Count Basie]], and led a [[big band]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Child prodigy===\nRich was born in [[Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn]], New York, to [[Jewish-American]] parents Bess Skolnik and Robert Rich, both [[vaudeville|vaudevillians]].<ref name=\"trapsbio\">{{cite book |last1=Torm\u00e9 |first1=Mel |title=Traps, the Drum Wonder: The Life of Buddy Rich |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-1888408034|page=6}}</ref> As a kid, when he was at a restaurant with his parents, he used the knife and fork as drum sticks. Before he turned two, he was part of his parents' act on vaudeville, but on breaks he would sneak into the orchestra pit and try to get the drummer's sticks. He was on Broadway as Baby Traps the Drum Wonder at age four, playing \"Stars and Stripes Forever\" on a drum.<ref name=\"Barron\">{{cite news |last1=Barron |first1=James |title=Buddy Rich, Jazz Drummer With Distinctive Sound, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/03/obituaries/buddy-rich-jazz-drummer-with-distinctive-sound-dies.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=3 April 1987}}</ref> He was a singer and tap dancer.<ref name=\"Yanow\" /> In his teens he led a band and toured in the U.S. and Australia. At fifteen he became the second highest paid child entertainer behind [[Jackie Coogan]] during the 1930s.<ref name=\"Barron\" />\n\n===Jazz career===\n[[File:Buddy Rich, New York, N.Y., ca. Aug. 1946 (William P. Gottlieb 07351)(cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Buddy Rich in New York City in August 1946]]\n\nHis jazz career began in 1937 with clarinetist [[Joe Marsala]]. He became a member of big bands led by [[Bunny Berigan]] and [[Artie Shaw]].<ref name=\"Yanow\" /><ref name=\"Barron\" /> When he was home from touring with Shaw, he gave drum lessons to a 14-year-old [[Mel Brooks]] for six months.<ref name=\"Howard\">{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Jeffrey K. |title=8/15/01: Lost Issue Mel Brooks Interview 1997 |url=http://www.filmscoremonthly.com/articles/2001/15_Aug---Lost_Issue_Mel_Brooks_Interview.asp |website=Filmscoremonthly.com |accessdate=19 November 2018 | date=15 August 2001 }}</ref> At 21, he participated in his first major recording with the [[Vic Schoen]] Orchestra who backed the [[Andrews Sisters]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/rich-buddy-bernard |title=Encyclopedia of Jazz &nbsp;\u2013 Buddy (Bernard) Rich |publisher=Jazz.com |accessdate=February 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219043015/http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/rich-buddy-bernard |archivedate=February 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1942, Rich left the Dorsey band to join the [[United States Marine Corps]], in which he served as a judo instructor, never saw combat, and was discharged due to medical reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1987-04-03/news/26193870_1_count-basie-band-buddy-rich-tommy-dorsey-band|title=A RICH TROVE OF BUDDY TALES DRUMMER WAS TRUE LEGEND|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> After leaving the Marines, he returned to the Dorsey band. In 1946, with financial support from Frank Sinatra, he formed a band and continued to lead bands intermittently until the early 1950s.<ref name=\"trapsbio\"/>{{rp|92, 95}}<ref>Jazz.com, Encyclopedia of Jazz Musicians, [http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/rich-buddy-bernard \"Buddy (Bernard) Rich\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219043015/http://www.jazz.com/encyclopedia/rich-buddy-bernard |date=February 19, 2011 }}; accessed February 28, 2010.</ref>\n\n[[File:Buddy Rich Bigband (Gottlieb 07391) (cropped).jpg|thumb|The Buddy Rich Big Band in the 1940s]]\n\nIn addition to Tommy Dorsey (1939\u201342, 1945, 1954\u201355), Rich played with [[Benny Carter]] (1942), [[Harry James]] (1953\u201356\u201362, 1964, 1965), [[Les Brown (bandleader)|Les Brown]], [[Charlie Ventura]], [[Jazz at the Philharmonic]], and [[Charlie Parker]] (''[[Bird and Diz]]'', 1950).\n\nFrom 1966 until his death, he led successful big bands in an era when their popularity had waned. He continued to play clubs but stated in interviews that the majority of his band's performances were at high schools, colleges, and universities rather than clubs. He was a session drummer for many recordings, where his playing was often more understated than in his big-band performances. Especially notable were sessions for [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Louis Armstrong]] and the [[Oscar Peterson]] trio with bassist [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]] and guitarist [[Herb Ellis]].<ref>louisarmstronghouse.org, \"Louis Armstrong House Museum\", [https://www.louisarmstronghouse.org/louie_armstrong/discography.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025175637/http://www.louisarmstronghouse.org/louie_armstrong/discography.htm |date=2014-10-25 }}; accessed October 30, 2014.</ref> In 1968, Rich collaborated with the Indian [[tabla]] player [[Ustad Alla Rakha]] on the album ''Rich \u00e0 la Rakha''.\n\nHe performed a big-band arrangement of a medley from ''[[West Side Story (musical)|West Side Story]]'' that was released on the 1966 album ''[[Swingin' New Big Band]]''. The \"West Side Story Medley\", arranged by Bill Reddie, is a complex big-band arrangement which highlights Rich's ability to blend the rhythm of his drumming into his band's playing of the musical chart. Rich received the West Side Story arrangement of [[Leonard Bernstein]]'s melodies from the famed [[Musical theater|musical]] in the mid-1960s and found it challenging. It consists of many difficult sections which feature 4/4 and 6/8 time signatures; it took almost a month of constant rehearsals to perfect. It later became a staple in all his performances, clocking in at various lengths from seven to fifteen minutes. A six-minute performance of \"Prologue/Jet Song\" from the suite, performed during Frank Sinatra's portion of the [[Concert for the Americas]], performed in the [[Altos de Chav\u00f3n]] amphitheater in the Dominican Republic on August 20, 1982 is on the DVD \"Frank Sinatra: Concert for the Americas\".<ref>.\"Frank Sinatra: Concert for the Americas\", Shout Factory LLC., 2012</ref> In 2002, a DVD was released called ''[[The Lost West Side Story Tapes]]'' that captured a 1985 performance of this along with other numbers.<ref name=\"Bowers\">{{cite web |last1=Jazz |first1=All About |title=Buddy Rich: The Lost Tapes |url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/buddy-rich-the-lost-tapes-by-jack-bowers.php |website=[[All About Jazz]] |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=9 December 2005}}</ref>\n\nA live recording of the \"Channel One Suite\" is on the album ''Mercy, Mercy'' recorded at [[Caesars Palace]] in 1968. The album received acclaim as the \"finest all-round recording by Buddy Rich's big band\".<ref name=\"mercy\">{{cite web |last1=Yanow |first1=Scott |title=Mercy, Mercy |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mercy-mercy-mw0000619226 |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=19 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===TV appearances===\nIn the 1950s Rich was a frequent guest on ''[[The Steve Allen Show]]'' and other television variety shows, most notably on [[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]. Rich and [[Johnny Carson|Johnny]] were lifelong friends and [[Johnny Carson]] was also a drum enthusiast himself.<ref>{{Citation|last=SanLouisKid|title=Johnny Carson Plays Drums|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0SS16APU65E|access-date=2019-01-06}}</ref><ref name=\"film\">{{cite book |last1=Yanow |first1=Scott |title=Jazz on Film |isbn=0-87930-783-8 |date=2004 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jazzonfilm00scot }}</ref><ref name=\"inventing\">{{cite book |last1=Alba |first1=Ben |title=Inventing Late Night: Steve Allen and the Original Tonight Show |date=2005 |publisher=Prometheus Books |isbn=1-59102-342-4}}</ref>\n\nIn 1973 PBS broadcast and syndicated Rich's February 6, 1973, performance at the Top of the Plaza in [[Rochester, New York]]. It was the first time thousands of drummers were exposed to Buddy in a full-length concert setting, and many drummers continue to name this program as a prime influence on their own playing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicforte.com/sheet_music/product/320338/BuddyRich-AttheTop|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021233440/http://www.musicforte.com/sheet_music/product/320338/BuddyRich-AttheTop/|url-status=dead|title=Buddy Rich \u2013 At the Top|archivedate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> One of his most widely seen television performances was in a 1981 episode of ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' in which he engaged Muppet drummer [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Animal|\"Animal\"]] (performed by [[Frank Oz]], drums played by [[Ronnie Verrell]]) in a drum battle.<ref name=\"Smith2013\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Gareth Dylan |title=I Drum, Therefore I Am: Being and Becoming a Drummer |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RNGvRymkGWQC&pg=PT71 |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=28 April 2013 |publisher=Ashgate |isbn=978-1-4094-7308-4|pages=71\u2013}}</ref> Rich's famous televised drum battles also included [[Gene Krupa]], [[Ed Shaughnessy]] and [[Louie Bellson]].<ref name=\"Smith2013\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nRich was married to Marie Allison, a dancer and showgirl on April 24, 1953, until his death in 1987. They had a daughter in 1954, Cathy, who later became a vocalist and carried on her father's band. Rich was also cousin of actor [[Jonathan Haze]].\n\nHe also lived in [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn]].<ref>Gluck, Robert. [https://www.algemeiner.com/2012/08/03/the-\u2018cinematic-zionism\u2019-of-mel-brooks/ \"The \u2018Cinematic Zionism\u2019 of Mel Brooks\"], ''[[The Algemeiner]]'', August 3, 2012. Accessed February 8, 2019. \"According to Wakeman, after World War II, Brooks started working in various Borscht Belt resorts and nightclubs as a drummer and pianist. Another Williamsburg resident, Buddy Rich, taught Brooks how to play drums and he started earning money that way at age 14.\"</ref>\n\n==Death==\nRich continued touring and performing until the end of his life. In early March 1987, he was touring in New York when he was hospitalized after suffering a paralysis on his left side that physicians believed had been caused by a stroke. He was transferred to California to UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles for tests, where doctors discovered and removed a brain tumor on March 16. He was discharged a week later, but had been receiving daily chemotherapy treatments at the hospital when, on April 2, 1987, he died of unexpected respiratory and cardiac failure after his treatment for the malignant brain tumor.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} His wife Marie and daughter Cathy buried him in [[Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]] in Los Angeles.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} He was 69.\n\n==Material loss==\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Buddy Rich among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite news |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personality==\nRich was notoriously short-tempered. Singer [[Dusty Springfield]] slapped him after several days of \"putting up with Rich's insults and show-biz sabotage\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dustyspringfield.info/2643.html |title=www.dustyspringfield.info |publisher=dustyspringfield.info |accessdate=February 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090303182600/http://dustyspringfield.info/2643.html |archivedate=March 3, 2009}}</ref> He held a rivalry with [[Frank Sinatra]] which sometimes ended in brawls when both were members of Tommy Dorsey's band. But they remained lifelong friends, and Sinatra delivered a eulogy at Rich's funeral in 1987.<ref name = \"drummerworld\">{{cite web |url=http://www.moderndrummer.com/site/2009/12/buddy-rich/|title=Buddy Rich: The World's Greatest Drummer |website=Moderndrummer.com|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nRich held a black belt in karate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/06/02/archives/how-buddy-rich-discovered-karate-and-tamed-his-temper-music-ever.html|title=Music|last=Wilson|first=John S.|date=1974-06-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-25|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n[[Billy Cobham]] said that he met Rich in a club and asked him to sign his snare drum; but Rich \u201cdropped it down the stairs\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/eb09778e-ca3c-11e3-bb92-00144feabdc0.html#axzz44l2VKGts |title=Interview: Drummer Billy Cobham and his fusion jazz career|publisher=ft.com|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to bassist [[Bill Crow]], Rich reacted strongly to [[Max Roach]]'s increasing popularity when he was the drummer for [[Charlie Parker]], especially when a jazz critic stated Roach had topped Rich as the world's greatest drummer.<ref name=\"Korall\">{{cite book |last1=Korall |first1=Burt |title=Drummin' Men: The Heartbeat of Jazz The Bebop Years |date=2004 |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=94}}</ref> Drummer [[John JR Robinson]] told Crow he was with Roach when Rich drove by with a beautiful woman seated next to him and yelled: \"Hey, Max! Top this!\".<ref name=\"Korall\" /> Nonetheless, the two worked together on the 1959 album ''[[Rich Versus Roach]]'', and Roach appeared on the 1994 Rich tribute album ''[[Burning for Buddy: A Tribute to the Music of Buddy Rich|Burning for Buddy]]''.\n\nRich preferred to concentrate on jazz and held a low opinion of both [[Country music|country]] and [[Rock music|rock]] music; during medical therapy before his death, a nurse asked Rich if he couldn't take anything (referring to medicine), to which he replied, \"Yeah, country  music.\"<ref name=\"Decker\">{{cite web |last1=Decker |first1=Cathleen |title=Buddy Rich, Frenetic Jazz Drummer, Dies |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-03/news/mn-2408_1_buddy-rich |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=3 April 1987}}</ref>\n\nRich's temper was documented in a series of secret recordings made on tour buses and in dressing rooms by pianist [[Lee Musiker]], who concealed a compact tape recorder in his clothing while on tour with Rich in the early 1980s.<ref name=\"Milkowski\">{{cite web |last1=Milkowski |first1=Bill |title=The Buddy Rich Tapes - JazzTimes |url=https://jazztimes.com/news/the-buddy-rich-tapes/ |website=JazzTimes |accessdate=20 November 2018 |date=1 March 2002}}</ref> On one recording, Rich threatens to fire trombonist [[Dave Panichi]] for having a beard.<ref name=\"Cooke\">{{cite web |last1=Cooke |first1=Richard |title=I Got Nothin' for You |url=https://www.themonthly.com.au/issue/2007/july/1274941799/richard-cooke/i-got-nothin-you |website=The Monthly |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en-gb |date=4 July 2007}}</ref> Although he threatened many times to fire members of his band, he seldom did so and for the most part, he praised his musicians in television and print interviews. The day before his death, April 1, 1987, Rich was visited by [[Mel Torm\u00e9]], who claims that one of Rich's last requests was to hear the tapes of his angry outbursts. Torm\u00e9 was working on an authorized biography of Rich, and included excerpts of the tapes in the book, but he never played the tapes for Rich.<ref name=trapsbio />{{rp|215}}\n\n==Influences, technique, and performances==\n[[File:Buddyrich.jpg|thumb|Buddy Rich performing at a concert in [[Cologne]], Germany on March 3, 1977]]\n\nRich cited [[Gene Krupa]], [[Jo Jones]], [[Chick Webb]], [[Ray McKinley]], [[Ray Bauduc]] and [[Sid Catlett]] as influences.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.drummerman.net/buddy.html | title= Gene Krupa and Buddy Rich interview | website=drummerman.net | accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe usually held his sticks with the [[traditional grip]]. He used the [[matched grip]] when playing [[floor tom]]s around the drum set while performing cross-stickings (crossing arm over arm), which was one of his party tricks, often leading to loud cheers from the audience. Another technique he used to impress was the stick-trick, a fast roll performed by slapping two drumsticks together in a circular motion using \"taps\" or single-stroke stickings. He often used contrasting techniques to keep long drum solos from getting mundane. Aside from his energetic, explosive displays, he would go into quieter passages. One passage he would use in most solos started with a simple single-stroke roll on the [[snare drum]] picking up speed and power, then slowly moving his sticks closer to the rim as he got quieter, and eventually playing on the rim itself while still maintaining speed. Then he would reverse the effect and slowly move towards the center of the snare while increasing power. Though well known as a powerful drummer, he did use [[Brush (music)|brushes]]. On the album ''[[The Lionel Hampton Art Tatum Buddy Rich Trio]]'' (1955) he played with brushes almost exclusively.\n\nIn 1942, Rich and [[Henry Adler]] wrote ''Buddy Rich's Modern Interpretation of Snare Drum Rudiments'', which is regarded as one of the more popular snare [[drum rudiment]] books.<ref name=\"legendary\">{{cite web |title=Henry Adler: Legendary Drum Teacher |url=https://www.moderndrummer.com/2011/02/henry-adler/ |website=Modern Drummer Magazine |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=4 February 2011}}</ref> Adler met Rich through a former student. Adler said, \"The kid told me he played better than Krupa. Buddy was only in his teens at the time and his friend was my first pupil. Buddy played and I watched his hands. Well, he knocked me right out. He did everything I wanted to do, and he did it with such ease. When I met his folks, I asked them who his teacher was. 'He never studied', they told me. That made me feel very good. I realized that it was something physical, not only mental, that you had to have.\"<ref name=\"Dinella\">{{cite web |last1=Dinella |first1=Jim |title=The World of Henry Adler |url=https://www.moderndrummer.com/article/march-1985-the-world-of-henry-adler/ |website=Modern Drummer Magazine |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=March 1985 }}</ref> Adler denied the rumor that he taught Rich how to play. \"Sure, he studied with me, but he didn't come to me to learn how to hold the drumsticks. I set out to teach Buddy to read. He'd take six lessons, go on the road for six weeks and come back. He didn't practice. He couldn't, because wherever the guy went, he was followed around by admiring drummers. He didn't have time to practice...Tommy Dorsey wanted Buddy to write a book and he told him to get in touch with me. I did the book and Tommy wrote the foreword. Technically, I was Buddy's teacher, but I came along after he had already acquired his technique.\"<ref name=\"Dinella\" />\n\nWhen asked if Rich could read music, [[Bobby Shew]], lead trumpeter in Rich's mid-1960s big band replied, \"No. He'd always have a drummer there during rehearsals to read and play the parts initially on new arrangements. Buddy would just sit in the empty audience seats in the afternoon and listen to the band...He'd only have to listen to a chart once and he'd have it memorized. We'd run through it and he'd know exactly how it went, how many measures it ran and what he'd have to do to drive it.\"<ref name=\"Myers\">{{cite web |last1=Myers |first1=Marc |title=Bobby Shew on Buddy Rich (Part 2) - JazzWax |url=https://www.jazzwax.com/2010/02/bobby-shew-on-budy-rich-part-2.html |website=Jazzwax.com |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=25 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' interview, Buddy had this to say about practicing: \"I don't put much emphasis on practice anyhow. I think it's a fallacy to believe that the more you practice, the better you become. You can only get better by playing. You can sit in a basement with a set of drums and practice rudiments all day long, but if you don't play with a band, you won't learn style, technique, and taste, and you won't learn how to play for a band and with a band. It's like getting a job, any kind of job, it's an opportunity to develop. And practice, besides that, is boring. I know teachers who tell their students to practice three, four, six hours a day. If you can't get what you want after an hour of practice, you're not going to get it in four days.\"{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn the same article, Rich also discourages playing drums with one's bare hands. When asked if he could do such a thing, he replied, 'Yes, but why destroy your hands? I could think of a hundred ways to use my hands rather than to break them on the rim of a drum.'\"{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n==Legacy==\nRich's technique, including speed, smooth execution and precision, is one of the most coveted in drumming and has become a common standard. [[Gene Krupa]] defined him as \"the greatest drummer ever to have drawn breath\".<ref name = \"drummerworld\"/>\n\nRich's influence extended from jazz to [[rock music]] and [[jazz fusion]]. He influenced drummers [[John Bonham]] of [[Led Zeppelin]],<ref name=\"bonham\">{{cite web |last1=Eder |first1=Bruce |title=John Bonham |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/john-bonham-mn0000218777/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref> [[Carl Palmer]] of [[Emerson, Lake & Palmer]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.classicrock-startpage.com/carlpalmerinterview.html |title= Carl Palmer interview |first= Clemens |last= Steenweg | publisher= classicrock-startpage.com |accessdate= 21 December 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043925/http://www.classicrock-startpage.com/carlpalmerinterview.html | archive-date= 4 March 2016 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref> [[Ian Paice]] of [[Deep Purple]],<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.thehighwaystar.com/interviews/paice/ip_mail_1999xxxx.html | title= An Exclusive Interview With Deep Purple's Drummer | first=Kevin J. | last=Julie | publisher=thehighwaystar.com | accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> [[Tr\u00e9 Cool]] from [[Green Day]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5y5nIyYJngo|title=Green Day induction ceremony @ Rock'n'Roll Hall Of Fame &#124; \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u0431\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0440\u044b InDub|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> and [[Bill Ward (musician)|Bill Ward]] of [[Black Sabbath]].<ref name=\"ward\">{{cite web |title=Thirsty: February 2010: Interview with Bill Ward of Black Sabbath |url=https://www.staythirstymedia.com/201002-042/html/201002-bill-ward-int.html |website=Staythirstymedia.com |accessdate=19 November 2018 |date=February 2010}}</ref> [[Phil Collins]] stopped using two [[bass drum]]s and started playing the [[hi-hat]] after reading Rich's opinion on the importance of the hi-hat.<ref name=\"Alexander\">{{cite journal |last1=Alexander |first1=Susan |title=Phil Collins on the Move |journal=Modern Drummer |date=March 1979}}</ref> [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], drummer of [[Queen (band)|Queen]], acknowledged Rich as the best drummer he ever saw for sheer technique.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/interviews/roger-taylor-1/drum-master-class/ | title= Roger's Drum Master Class (Music Works - BBC World Service, November 28 1993) | publisher=Queen Online | accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref> [[Blink-182]] drummer [[Travis Barker]] has credited Rich as the greatest drummer of all time.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g-eX0HR1syE</ref>\n\nSince Rich's death, a number of memorial concerts have been held. In 1994, the Rich tribute album ''[[Burning for Buddy: A Tribute to the Music of Buddy Rich]]'' was released. Produced by [[Rush (band)|Rush]] drummer/lyricist [[Neil Peart]], the album features performances of Rich staples by a number of jazz and rock drummers such as [[Joe Morello]], [[Steve Gadd]], [[Max Roach]], [[Billy Cobham]], [[Dave Weckl]], [[Simon Phillips (drummer)|Simon Phillips]], [[Steve Smith (musician)|Steve Smith]], and Peart himself, accompanied by the Buddy Rich Big Band. A [[Burning for Buddy: A Tribute to the Music of Buddy Rich, Vol. 2|second volume]] was issued in 1997. Phil Collins was featured in a DVD tribute organized by Rich's daughter, ''A Salute to Buddy Rich'', which included Steve Smith and [[Dennis Chambers]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.allaboutjazz.com/a-salute-to-buddy-rich-by-john-kelman.php | title= A Salute To Buddy Rich | work=All About Jazz| first=John | last=Kelman | date=14 July 2004 | accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nOn September 30, 2017, Rich was honored with a Star on the Palm Springs Walk of Stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmspringslife.com/drumroll-please/|title=Buddy Rich Earns Palm Springs Tribute|publisher=Palm Springs Life|accessdate=September 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, readers of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine ranked Rich No. 15 in their list of the 100 Greatest Drummers of all time.<ref name=\"2016poll\">{{cite web|title=100 Greatest Drummers of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-drummers-of-all-time-20160331/bill-bruford-20160328|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=8 June 2017|date=31 March 2016}}</ref> In a readers' poll in 2011, he ranked No. 6.<ref name=\"2011poll\">{{cite web|title=Rolling Stone Readers Pick the Best Drummers of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/pictures/rolling-stone-readers-pick-best-drummers-of-all-time-20110208/5-ringo-starr-0875383|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=8 June 2017|date=8 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As leader/co-leader===\n* 1953: ''[[The Flip Phillips Buddy Rich Trio]]'' ([[Clef Records|Clef]])<ref>Norgran, Clef, Verve, Mercury, Pacific Jazz, etc. discographies at [http://www.jazzdisco.org/ jazzdisco.org]</ref>\n* 1954: ''[[The Swinging Buddy Rich]]'' ([[Norgran Records|Norgran]])\n* 1955: ''[[Sing and Swing with Buddy Rich]]'' (Norgran)\n* 1955: ''[[Buddy and Sweets]]'' (Norgran)\n* 1955: ''[[The Lester Young Buddy Rich Trio]]'' (Norgran)\n* 1955: ''[[The Wailing Buddy Rich]]'' (Norgran)\n* 1955: ''[[Krupa and Rich]]'' (Clef)\n* 1955: ''[[The Lionel Hampton Art Tatum Buddy Rich Trio]]'' (Clef)\n* 1956: ''[[Buddy Rich Sings Johnny Mercer]]'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]])\n* 1956: ''[[This One's for Basie]]'' (Verve) re-issued 1967 as ''Big Band Shout''<ref>[http://www.hepjazz.com/bios/buddyrich.html] {{dead link|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n* 1957: ''[[Buddy Rich Just Sings]]'' (Verve)\n* 1958: ''[[Buddy Rich in Miami]]'' (Verve)\n* 1959: ''[[Richcraft]]'' ([[Mercury Records|Mercury]]) \u2013 also ''[[The Rich Rebellion]]'' ([[Wing Records|Wing]])\n* 1959: ''[[Rich Versus Roach]]'' (Mercury)\n* 1959: ''[[The Voice is Rich]]'' (Mercury)\n* 1960: ''[[The Driver (Buddy Rich album)|The Driver]]'' ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]])\n* 1961: ''[[Playtime (album)|Playtime]]'' ([[Argo Records|Argo]])\n* 1961: ''[[Blues Caravan]]'' (Verve)\n* 1962: ''[[Burnin' Beat]]'' (Verve)\n* 1965: ''[[Are You Ready for This?]]'' ([[Roost Records|Roost]])\n* 1966: ''[[Swingin' New Big Band]]'' ([[Pacific Jazz Records|Pacific Jazz]]/[[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]])\n* 1966: ''[[The Sounds of '66]]'' ([[Reprise Records|Reprise]])\n* 1967: ''[[Big Swing Face (Buddy Rich album)|Big Swing Face]]'' (Pacific Jazz) \n* 1967: ''[[The New One!]]'' (Pacific Jazz) \u2013 a.k.a. ''Take it Away''\n* 1968: ''[[Rich \u00e0 la Rakha]]'' (World Pacific)\n* 1968: ''[[Mercy, Mercy (album)|Mercy, Mercy]]'' (Pacific Jazz)\n* 1969: ''[[Buddy & Soul]]'' Recorded Live in Hollywood At The Whiskey A Go Go (Pacific Jazz)\n* 1970: ''[[Keep the Customer Satisfied (album)|Keep the Customer Satisfied]]'' ([[Liberty Records|Liberty]])\n* 1971: ''[[A Different Drummer (album)|A Different Drummer]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]]) \u2013 a.k.a. ''Superstar''\n* 1971: ''[[Rich in London]]'' (RCA) \u2013 expanded UK release \u2013 ''Buddy Rich: Very Alive at Ronnie Scott's'' (RCA (UK)) \n* 1971: ''[[Conversations (Buddy Rich, Louie Bellson, Kenny Clare album)|Conversations]]'' ([[EMI]]-[[Parlophone]])\n* 1972: ''[[Stick It (Buddy Rich album)|Stick It]]'' (RCA)\n* 1973: ''[[The Roar of '74]]'' ([[Groove Merchant]])\n* 1974: ''[[Very Live at Buddy's Place]]'' (Groove Merchant)\n* 1974: ''[[Transition (Buddy Rich Lionel Hampton album)|Transition]]'' (Groove Merchant)\n* 1974: ''[[The Last Blues Album Volume 1]]'' (Groove Merchant)\n* 1975: ''[[Big Band Machine]]'' (Groove Merchant)\n* 1976: ''[[Speak No Evil (Buddy Rich album)|Speak No Evil]]'' (RCA)\n* 1977: ''[[Buddy Rich Plays and Plays and Plays]]'' (RCA)\n* 1977: ''[[Lionel Hampton Presents Buddy Rich]]'' ([[Who's Who in Jazz]]) \u2013 a.k.a. ''Buddy's Cherokee...'' also released as ''The Sound of Jazz, Vol 10''\n* 1977: ''[[Class of '78]]'' ([[The Great American Gramophone Company]]) \u2013 also released as ''The Greatest Drummer That Ever Lived with The Best Band I Ever Had''\n* 1978: ''[[Together Again: For the First Time]]'' Buddy Rich, Mel Torm\u00e9 (Gryphon/Century) \u2013 a.k.a. ''When I Found You''\n* 1980: ''[[Live at Ronnie Scott's (Buddy Rich album)|Live at Ronnie Scott's]]'' (DRG) \u2013 Live. a.k.a. ''The Man from Planet Jazz''\n* 1981: ''[[The Buddy Rich Band]]'' ([[MCA Records|MCA]])\n* 1982: ''[[Buddy Rich, Live at the 1982 Montreal Jazz Festival|Live at the 1982 Montreal Jazz Festival]]'' (Hudson Music)\n* 1983: ''[[Rich and Famous (Buddy Rich album)|Rich and Famous]]'' (Amway) \u2013 a.k.a. ''The Magic of Buddy Rich'', a.k.a. ''Buddy Rich \u2013 The Man''\n* 1985: ''[[Mr. Drums: Buddy Rich & His Band Live on King Street|Mr. Drums: ...Live on King Street]]'' ([[Mobile Fidelity Sound Lab|Cafe]])\n\n===Posthumous albums===\n* 1993: ''Europe '77'' (Magic)\n* 1996: ''Buddy Rich & His Big Band At Stadthalle Leonberg, Germany 10 July 1986'' (Jazz Band)\n* 2001: ''Wham! The Buddy Rich Big Band Live'' (Label M)\n* 2004: ''No Funny Hats'' (Lightyear)\n* 2007: ''Time Out'' (Lightyear)\n* 2009: ''Buddy Rich Up Close'' (Drum Channel)\n* 2014: ''The Solos'' (Lightyear Entertainment)\n* 2015: ''Birdland'' (Lightyear Entertainment)\n* 2019: ''Just In Time: The Final Recording'' (Gearbox Records)\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* 1960: ''The Drum Battle (Gene Krupa and Buddy Rich at [[Jazz at the Philharmonic|JATP]])'' (Verve)\n* 1964: ''The Best of Buddy Rich'' (Pacific Jazz)\n* 1969: ''Super Rich'' (Verve)\n* 1971: ''Time Being'' (Bluebird/RCA)\n* 1987: ''Compact Jazz: Buddy Rich'' (Verve)\n* 1990: ''Compact Jazz: Gene Krupa & Buddy Rich'' (Verve)\n* 1992: ''No Jive'' (Novus)\n* 1998: ''Buddy Rich: The Legendary '47\u2013'48 Orchestra Vol. 1'' (Hep)\n* 1998: ''Buddy Rich: The Legendary '46\u2013'48 Orchestra Vol. 2'' (Hep)\n* 2005: ''Classic EmArcy, Verve, Small Group Buddy Rich Sessions'' ([[Mosaic Records|Mosaic]] No.&nbsp;232)\n\n===As sideman===\n'''With [[Count Basie]]'''\n* ''[[Basie Jazz]]'' ([[Clef Records|Clef]], 1952 [1954])\n* ''[[The Swinging Count!]]'' (Clef 1952 [1956]